<DOCNO> AP890722-0010 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-22-89 0642EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-Names     07-22 0914</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Names,0950</SECOND>
<HEAD>Names in the News</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY14</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Marvin Hamlisch may have three Oscars and a Tony
award, but he took a right jab to the ego when his wife, Terre
Blair, called her mother to say they were going to get married this
past spring.
   ``She said, `What's his name?' '' Mrs. Hamlisch recalled on
Friday's ``CBS This Morning.'' ``And I said Marvin Hamlisch. And
she said, `Isn't he a boxer in Las Vegas?'
   ``She thought he was Marvin Hagler, she'd never heard of him
before. Then I said to her, `No, he's a composer _ he writes songs
and he tours. And she said, `Just what this family needs, an
out-of-work songwriter.'''
   Hamlisch, 45, won a Tony for the score to ``A Chorus Line'' and
Academy Awards for the adapted score of ``The Sting'' and two more
for his work on ``The Way We Were.''
   Hamlisch said he fell in love with Ms. Blair on the phone and
proposed without having met her. They were married May 29.
   ``I said, `Will you _ sight unseen _ marry me?''' he said.
``Thankfully, she said yes.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal appeals court has refused to
reinstate a libel suit by ``Miami Vice'' star Philip Michael Thomas
against the National Enquirer for articles about his upbringing and
his family.
   The 9th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals on Friday upheld a U.S.
District Court ruling in the tabloid's favor.
   The National Enquirer printed an article in December 1985
describing the 1980 rape conviction of his brother, Marcus Thomas,
and the family's role in his appeal. The second article, published
in the tabloid a month later, said Philip Michael Thomas had grown
up in poverty and was a ``mama's boy.''
   The suit said the first article invaded the family's privacy and
the second was also libelous.
   U.S. District Judge William Orrick of San Francisco ruled two
years ago that the suit over the first article was filed too late,
and that the second article was not libelous.
   The appeals court said the statements in the second article were
``substantially true'' or, if untrue, did not defame the family.
   Thomas played detective Rico Tubbs on the television series.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>KINGSPORT, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Singer Nicollette Larson's first job in
the music business got her closer to the industry than many young
hopefuls.
   Miss Larson boarded a bus from her native Kansas City and headed
to California 16 years ago to seek her musical fortune.
   At 21, she landed a job as a secretary for the Golden State
Bluegrass Festival. It wasn't long before Miss Larson's singing
ability overshadowed her typing speed.
   ``Actually from the time I left Kansas City until I had a hit
record was only about four years,'' she said in a recent interview.
``I was actually pretty lucky.''
   Miss Larson's first No. 1 hit, ``Lotta Love,'' was in 1978. More
recent tunes include ``Rumba Girl,'' ``Fool Me Again'' and ``I Only
Want to be With You.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>JOHNSON CITY, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Timothy Busfield, who portrays Elliot
Weston, the yuppie everybody loves to hate on television's
``Thirtysomething,'' says he is fond of his character.
   ``I love Elliot,'' Busfield said. ``He doesn't want to grow up,
but that's good. Why should he have to grow up?''
   Busfield, 32, is conducting a theater workshop at East Tennessee
State University for high school and college students. He is
scheduled to appear next week in a production at the school of
``Mass Appeal,'' the story of a priest and a fiery young seminary
student. Busfield plays the student.
   Actors have a job that has little to do with stardom, Busfield
said.
   ``It's not to star or to get attention or to be the most
popular, but it's to make the play work,'' he said. ``The
playwright did not have you in mind when he wrote the play.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>MANSFIELD, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sylvester Stallone and Kurt Russell spent
some time behind bars to film a scene for their new movie.
   The two stars were at the Ohio State Reformatory on Friday to
film an escape scene for the movie ``Setup,'' which Warner Bros.
expects to release in early August.
   Russell, asked at a news conference about his work behind prison
walls, said: ``I've never worked inside a prison before. Obviously,
it's some place I don't want to spend the rest of my life.''
   Both Stallone and Russell play policemen in the movie.
   Warden Eric Dahlberg said 20 to 30 prisoners appeared in the
film.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>DAYTON, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Brigadier Gen. Frank K. Everest Jr., an Air
Force test pilot who set an unofficial speed record is scheduled to
be inducted into the the National Aviation Hall of Fame tonight.
   Three other aviation leaders _ Chance Vought, Adm. Marc A.
Mitscher and Lloyd C. Stearman _ were to be posthumously inducted
into the hall of fame at the ceremony led by Sen. John Glenn,
D-Ohio.
   Everest, who retired from the Air Force in 1973, tested many
airplanes, including the X-1, X-2, X-3, F-100, F-101, and F-102. He
attained the unofficial speed record of 1,957 mph in the X-2.
   Vought, who died in 1930, designed the UO-1, the Navy's first
catapult-launched aircraft. Mitscher, who died in 1947, made the
first aircraft takeoff and landing on the USS Saratoga in 1928.
Stearman joined with others in purchasing the Lockheed Aircraft Co.
in 1930 and later designed the Lockheed Electra. He died in 1970.
