<FIRST>r w PM-DefenseBill     07-22 0488</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Defense Bill,400</SECOND>
<HEAD>Appropriations Subcommittee Votes Cuts in B-2, Star Wars</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Stealth Bomber</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KIM I. MILLS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A House committee will consider cutting $500
million from President Bush's budget for the B-2 stealth bomber in
the newest sign of congressional opposition to the high cost of the
radar-evading aircraft.
   A source, speaking on condition of anonymity, said Friday the
Appropriations defense subcommittee voted to make the cuts in
closed session as part of a package of changes in Bush's defense
budget.
   The source said the panel also voted Thursday to cut Star Wars
by $1.1 million and to fund the V-22 Osprey and the F-14D fighter,
two programs the administration has earmarked for extinction.
   The measure, which now goes to the full Appropriations
Committee, also included funds to purchase 12 EA-6 jet fighters,
the source said.
   The Defense Department is asking for $4.7 billion for the B-2,
which will carry a price tag of $530 million per plane. The House
Armed Services Committee last month cut the overall request by $800
million.
   The action by the Appropriations subcommittee would still leave
$4.2 billion for the plane.
   Bush has gotten personally involved in the lobbying effort,
telling groups of congressmen at the White House this week the B-2
is necessary to the nation's security.
   In the case of the F-14D, the committee coupled its approval of
$1.3 billion for 24 planes with a recommendation to close the
production line at Grumman Corp. in Bethpage, N.Y., in three years.
   ``Instead of doing 12 this year and 12 next year, which was the
Armed Services Committee plan, we said `Fund 'em all up front,
deliver 'em over three years and begin the orderly closedown of the
line,''' the source said.
   The $500 million cut from Bush's B-2 request came from
purchasing funds, according to the source. That would leave $2.2
billion in purchasing funds for the B-2 and $2 billion for research
and development.
   The black, wedge-shaped bomber made its first successful test
flight this week, but still faces opposition from lawmakers who
fear the planes could wind up costing up to $1 billion apiece.
   The subcommittee called for $157 million for the Osprey. The
administration wants to cancel it, saying conventional helicopters
could serve the same purpose as the tilt-wing rotorcraft, which
takes off like a helicopter and flies like a plane.
   On Star Wars, the Strategic Defense Initiative, the subcommittee
called for $3.5 billion, considerably less than the $4.6 billion
Bush proposed.
   The Senate Armed Services Committee voted last week to accept
Defense Secretary Dick Cheney's proposal to eliminate the F-14D.
   Long Island, N.Y., legislators have been lobbying hard all year,
trying to keep the F-14D alive on the grounds that closing the line
would cost some 5,100 jobs on Long Island and would effectively put
the Grumman Corp. out of the aircraft business. Grumman also builds
the EA-6 jet fighter.
</TEXT>
