<FIRST>r w PM-OilSpills-Congress     07-22 0303</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Oil Spills-Congress,300</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mitchell, Skinner Clash Over Oil Spill Legislation</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROSE ANN ROBERTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Some state officials want Congress to resist
pressure from the Exxon Valdez accident and allow local authorities
to decide how to handle oil spills.
   The attorneys general from three states differed sharply with
Transportation Secretary Samuel K. Skinner, who told a
congressional panel Friday that stronger federal rules are the only
way to ensure the United States is compensated for spills by
foreign tankers.
   ``To argue that state laws offer a viable alternative to
(international treaties) is to ignore the facts,'' Skinner told the
Senate Environment and Public Works environmental protection
subcommittee.
   The administration wants to strengthen federal law and ratify
two international treaties involving payment for damages resulting
from oil spills caused by foreign tankers.
   But the local officials say those closest to tanker traffic and
accidents know best how to deal with the consequences.
   ``Pre-empting our state law and requiring us to ... rely on a
system administered by the federal government is not a proposal
which can be accepted by the state of Maine,'' Maine Attorney
General James E. Tierney said.
   ``Even if coupled with an international fund, the result (of the
treaties) would be that in some situations, damages would go
uncompensated because state law protection is unavailable,''said
Alaska Attorney General Douglas B. Baily.
   Tierney and Bailey were joined by Washington state Attorney
General Kenneth O. Eikenberry.
   Attempts to tighten regulations on fuel tankers have picked up
speed since the Exxon tanker Valdez ran aground March 24 in
Alaska's Prince William Sound, spilling nearly 11 million gallons
of Alaska crude into the water.
   Kenneth R. Dickerson, an Arco Oil Co. senior vice president,
told the panel his company supports giving the federal government
sole responsibility for oil-spill cleanups.
</TEXT>
