<DOCNO> AP890722-0017 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-22-89 0301EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-StealthBomber     07-22 0580</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Stealth Bomber,550</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Says B-2 Crucial to START Talks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONNA CASSATA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Bush administration, facing pressure from
lawmakers opposed to the costly B-2 bomber, is raising the stakes
by arguing that halting the program would be ``devastating to arms
control efforts.''
   In meetings at the White House and on Capitol Hill Friday,
officials told congressmen that the failure to fund the stealth
bomber would force the United States to withdraw its proposal in
strategic arms reduction talks with the Soviet Union.
   The coordinated effort for the radar-evading aircraft was in
evidence all over the Capitol. The pilots who guided the B-2 on its
first flight Monday _ Air Force Col. Rich Couch and Northrop Corp.
test pilot Bruce Hinds _ appeared before a Senate Armed Services
subcommittee and later met with members of Congress.
   Elsewhere, Defense Secretary Dick Cheney and Adm. William Crowe,
chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff, met with lawmakers to plead
their case for the bomber.
   President Bush told House Republicans at a White House lobbying
session that stopping the $70 billion program would be
``devastating to arms control efforts,'' according to one
congressman in attendance, Rep. William Dickinson of Alabama.
   But some members remained unswayed.
   ``I was not convinced by the president's remarks,'' Rep. John
Rowland, R-Conn., said. ``There are a small number of Republicans
and hopefully a large number of Democrats'' who believe testing
should be completed before a commitment is made to build the 132
planes the Pentagon wants.
   ``By 1993 we will have purchased 44 planes'' at a cost of $40
billion, Rowland said. He said it is best to build a few, ``fly
them around ... develop them and then make a determination.''
   Rowland; Rep. John Kasich, R-Ohio; and Rep. Ronald Dellums,
D-Calif., plan to introduce an amendment next week to the defense
bill to build only 13 bombers.
   Rowland said Bush rejected the offer.
   The White House has also rejected a proposal by Rep. Les Aspin,
D-Wis., chairman of the House Armed Services Committee, to pay for
just two bombers in 1990 and 1991 and not the eight sought by the
Pentagon. Aspin argues Congress needs more information on the plane
before deciding whether to kill it or spend more money.
   House Speaker Thomas S. Foley, D-Wash., indicated his support
for the Aspin plan Friday.
   ``I think if I were voting I would probably be inclined to
support (it),'' he told reporters. ``I think we should not stop
this program, but we should have an opportunity to review it in the
near future.''
   The Pentagon has invested about $23 billion in the program and
hopes to purchase 132 bombers at a cost of about $70 billion.
   But lawmakers have suffered ``sticker shock'' from the price tag
_ $530 million for a single plane.
   For fiscal 1990, the Defense Department proposed spending $4.7
billion for the B-2, but the House Armed Services Committee last
month cut that by $800 million.
   Separately, a congressional source who requested anonymity said
Friday that a House Appropriations subcommittee voted Thursday to
strike $500 million in B-2 funds from the authorization bill.
   The argument that failure to build the B-2 would undermine the
START negotiations, which are aimed at reducing U.S. and Soviet
strategic or long-range bombers, missiles and nuclear submarines by
30 to 50 percent, raised the ire of at least one Senate Armed
Services Committee member.
   Sen. Timothy Wirth, D-Colo., called it ``almost legislative
blackmail.''
</TEXT>
