<FIRST>r a PM-Spokesman-Banks     07-22 0294</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Spokesman-Banks,290</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former Aide to Roth, Rinaldo Charged With Bank Robbery</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BETHESDA, MD. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former press aide to two members of
Congress is facing charges he robbed two suburban Washington, D.C.,
banks.
   Thomas Springer, 40, was charged Thursday with three counts of
armed robbery, including two robberies at one branch of the
Maryland National Bank in Bethesda, Md., Montgomery County police
said Friday.
   Springer was arrested Thursday morning in a wooded area near
that bank shortly after what police said was the second robbery.
   Police spokesman Sgt. Harry Geehreng said a man carrying a box
entered the bank about 10:30 a.m. and handed a teller a note saying
he had a bomb and wanted money. The man fled through a back door
with an undisclosed amount of cash.
   Springer was arrested shortly afterward, police said.
   Springer, of Silver Spring, Md., was also was charged with
robbing the same branch on April 14 and a Crestar Bank branch in
Bethesda on May 12, police said.
   He was held in the Montgomery County jail in lieu of $50,000
bond.
   Springer was a longtime press secretary to Rep. Toby Roth,
R-Wis., the congressman said Friday.
   Springer left his press job in 1987, but was later given a
temporary assignment in the office, a Roth aide said.
   Roth said he gave Springer the temporary job ``because I felt
sorry for him,'' but that Springer then failed to show up for work.
   ``I am deeply saddened,'' Roth said, adding that Springer's
``behavior had deteriorated'' in recent years.
   Springer also worked for Rep. Matthew Rinaldo, R-N.J., on a
temporary basis, according to a statement from Rinaldo. ``Tom
Springer worked here for a very short time and while he was here
his work was satisfactory,'' the statement said.
</TEXT>
