<FIRST>u w PM-WashingtoninBrief     07-22 0814</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Washington in Brief,780</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former President Will Mediate 28-Year-Old Conflict</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former President Carter will travel to
Ethiopia next week to serve as a mediator between the government
and Eritrean rebels in an effort to resolve their long-running
conflict, a U.S. diplomat says.
   Assistant Secretary of State Herman Cohen on Friday said Carter
had been accepted by both the Marxist government of Haile Mengistu
Mariam and by the Eritrean rebels who have been warring against the
government for 28 years in one of Africa's longest-running civil
wars.
   Cohen told reporters a dialogue between the two sides would make
it easier for the United States to improve relations with
Mengistu's government, which have been strained since the early
1980s when Mengistu shifted his country's alliances to the Soviet
Union.
   The Soviets have been pressing Mengistu to negotiate with the
rebels and end the costly war in an effort to cut Soviet aid to
Ethiopia.
   Carter visited Ethiopia earlier this year and met with Mengistu.
In recent years, the former president has been a mediator and
observer in foreign conflicts.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>Bunker Hunt Blames Banks For Partnership At Heart of Tax Dispute</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Texas oilman Nelson Bunker Hunt is blaming his
bank creditors for forcing on him and his brothers a partnership to
handle the repayment of his enormous silver debts.
   The deal is at the heart of a $300 million dispute with the
Internal Revenue Service, which contends the partnership was a sham.
   Hunt said Friday the banks ``pretty much took over for a while
and dictated'' his affairs after Silver Thursday, the day in late
March 1980 when silver prices tumbled from a high of $50 an ounce
to $10 an ounce.
   ``The net effect was we didn't have control over our business.
That's why I'm sitting here in court, because the structure the
banks put us in,'' Hunt told U.S. Tax Court Judge Jules G. Korner
III.
   Hunt is contesting $155 million in 1982 taxes the IRS claims are
due from the dissolution of the partnership he and his brothers set
up after Silver Thursday to repay as much as $2 billion on their
soured silver investments.
   Brother William Herbert Hunt is contesting more than $158
million in 1982 taxes, while Lamar, owner of the Kansas City Chiefs
football team, is contesting $505,377.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>House Easily OKs Bill, Sends It To The Senate</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The House has approved a $14.3 billion foreign
aid bill that sends a warning to the Philippines to improve its
management of aid dollars and begins President Bush's initiatives
in Hungary and Poland to boost private development.
   The lawmakers voted 329 to 69 Friday to approve what
traditionally has been one of the most contentious pieces of
legislation Congress takes up each year. The bill, one of 13 basic
money measures that fund the full array of federal programs, goes
to the Senate next.
   The measure includes $160 million as the U.S. contribution
toward the Multilateral Assistance Initiative for the Philippines,
an effort to bolster the government of President Corazon Aquino
with an influx of development aid.
   But that amount falls below the $200 million pledged to the
program by President Bush. The cut was intended to signal concerns
that money already flowing to the Philippines is not being used or
is being wasted.
   The measure includes $10 million for Poland and $5 million for
Hungary to begin a three-year, $125-million plan announced by Bush
last week to encourage private development in those two East Bloc
countries.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>Four Officials Told They'll Be Dismissed</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Four Department of Housing and Urban
Development officials are being fired as part of the department's
investigation of mismanagement and cronyism during the Reagan
administration.
   Three were told Friday that they will be dismissed in 30 days
unless they can refute charges of mismanagement against them, and a
fourth, who is out of town, will be told next Tuesday, HUD
officials disclosed.
   The members of the department's troubled Washington field office
are the first people dismissed in connection with the probe.
   The Washington field office was the base of operations of escrow
agent Marilyn Harrell, who became known as ``Robin HUD'' after she
confessed to diverting $5.5 million of the department's money to
charities.
   The four officials were placed on leave in June, then given
temporary assignments at headquarters when their leaves expired
earlier this month.
   They are Margaret White, former head of the office; Robert B.
Warner, director of housing management; Charles W. Womble, loan
specialist; and Everett Rothschild, head of property disposition.
   An audit of the office found that lax financial and management
controls allowed agents like Ms. Harrell to delay transfers of
funds or not make them at all. Auditors have estimated the office
is missing a total of $10 million.
   Rothschild will be given his letter on Tuesday, the officials
said.
</TEXT>
