<FILEID>AP-NR-07-22-89 0322EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-CentennialCanoes     07-22 0491</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Centennial Canoes,0504</SECOND>
<HEAD>Indians From Far Reaches Make Final Leg on `Paddle To Seattle'</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto SE1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM KLAHN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SUQUAMISH, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Indians from the coasts of western
Washington and British Columbia crossed Puget Sound in a flotilla
of some two dozen traditional canoes on the last leg of the
``Paddle to Seattle.''
   Participants _ paddlers, chiefs and canoe-builders _ said Friday
they hoped the trip in hand-carved cedar vessels also was a
celebration of a reawakening of Indian customs and traditions.
   ``It's a taste of our ancestors,'' said Chuck Harrison, a
Quileute Indian who had made the 179-mile trip from LaPush, on the
Washington coast. ``It makes us proud to be Indians _ Hoh and
Quileutes.''
   The Quileutes and Hohs, from the mouth of the Hoh River, paddled
together on the journey, which is part of the state's centennial
celebrations. The Quileutes retraced a route used for trade early
this century, and invited other tribes to join them in what became
known as the ``Paddle to Seattle.''
   Many other tribes took up the invitation, and the flotilla on
the seven-mile trip Friday from Suquamish to Golden Gardens in
north Seattle represented canoes from as near as Suquamish and as
far away as Bella Bella, on the British Columbia coast 100 miles
north of Vancouver Island.
   Some ocean-going canoes carried as many as 18 people. The
smallest dugout carried a single paddler.
   The arrival of the canoes in Seattle on Friday signaled the
beginning of a weekend of canoe racing, dancing and eating at
salmon bakes.
   The meeting of the tribes was a special time, said Jerry Jones,
designer of the Tulalip tribe's canoe.
   ``We hope that this will be a start to bring back our culture
and heritage,'' he said. ``I hope that 150 years from now our
descendants will still be paddling canoes and not forget they are
Indian.''
   He said the last large canoe carved by the Tulalips was turned
out 70 years ago, and he had to learn the skills of canoe-building
as he went. Jones said he hoped to pass traditions down to others
of his tribe in a book on building canoes.
   Others at the gathering said using the canoes was a new
experience, nearly lost in the age of their grandparents.
   ``It's a neat experience I never had,'' said Roger Sullivan, a
Port Klallam Indian. ``It's a tradition that will come back, I
hope.''
   The Indians coming the farthest _ nearly 400 miles _ were
members of the Heiltsuk Nation near Bella Bella. Frank Brown, of
the Heiltsuk, said his tribe had issued a challenge to other
Northwest tribes to meet at Bella Bella four years from now ``and
talk about where we want to go as a people.''
   At least some accepted the challenge.
   ``We gave them a Quileute paddle, that we have to get back'' by
going to Bella Bella, said Henry Lee Morganroth, a Quileute paddler.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
