<FIRST>r a PM-NOW-Abortion     07-22 0296</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-NOW-Abortion,0306</SECOND>
<HEAD>NOW Planning Pro-Abortion Strategy</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN NOLAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CINCINNATI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The recent Supreme Court ruling on abortion
has boosted membership in the National Organization for Women and
the group said it will push for legislation to prevent states from
restricting abortions.
   NOW President Molly Yard outlined the organization's plans at a
Friday news conference opening its annual conference.
   Ms. Yard said a surge of activism sparked by the high court's
July 3 decision has created interest in NOW in recent weeks.
Membership has grown from about 160,000 last year to 200,000, she
said.
   The court granted states some powers to restrict access to
abortions.
   ``People are angry,'' Ms. Yard said. ``They are angry that
someone would come into their lives, into so personal a decision as
when, and if, to have children.''
   Outside the conference at the Cincinnati Convention Center, a
dozen abortion opponents picketed.
   NOW lawyers are working on a proposal, which could take the form
of a bill or constitutional amendment, to prohibit states from
interfering with women's rights to have abortions, Ms. Yard said.
The organization hopes to have the proposal introduced in Congress
in September.
   Ms. Yard said NOW, using an approach that abortion opponents
have used in the past, would campaign to defeat lawmakers who
oppose women's right to abortion.
   ``Have you watched politicians running for cover ever since July
3?'' she said. ``We intend, on the national and state level, to
fight those who would deny women the freedom to control their
reproductive lives and who would deny us equal rights under the
Constitution. ... That is the message of the women's movement.''
   Ms. Yard said NOW will work against President Bush because the
group regards him as being an opponent of women's rights.
</TEXT>
