<FILEID>AP-NR-07-22-89 0431EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Cambodia-Attack 1stLd-Writethru a0446 07-22 0406</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Cambodia-Attack, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0446,0416</SECOND>
<HEAD>Casualties Reported as Shells Hit Khmer Rouge Refugee Camp</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 9 grafs to upgrade attribution, add details; picks
up 10th pvs, `On Friday...'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Shellfire hit a Khmer Rouge refugee
camp on the Thai-Cambodian border for a second day today, killing
up to four people and forcing thousands to flee, a U.N. relief
official said.
   The shelling came in two separate morning attacks, said Patrick
Van de Velde, deputy director of the U.N. Border Relief Operation.
He cited unconfirmed reports as saying seven people were wounded
and four killed.
   Other Western officials said pro-Vietnamese forces apparently
staged the attacks as well as shelling Friday that killed one
refugee and wounded 10 others.
   The shelling, the heaviest ever on Site 8, could be intended to
gain bargaining power at the peace talks to open in Paris on
Monday, the officials said.
   Site 8, home to about 40,000 Cambodians, is about 156 miles east
of Bangkok, separated from Cambodia by sheer rocky cliffs.
   Populated mostly by women and children, it is the main civilian
camp run by the communist Khmer Rouge, the largest guerrilla group
fighting the Vietnamese-supported army in Cambodia.
   In the past, the Khmer Rouge has shelled its own camps as part
of its attempts to exercise strict control over the refugees.
Widespread human rights violations have been reported.
   Van de Velde said the refugees first sought shelter from the
shelling at the base of the cliffs or along a road leading to Site
8. Later, they all gathered in an open area about a mile further
inside Thailand, he said.
   ``We are sending emergency supplies to help them build temporary
shelters,'' Van de Velde said.
   On Friday, a 22-year-old man was killed and 10 other refugees
wounded, including two small children, when 27 or 28 shells crashed
into the camp, a Red Cross official said.
   Fighting between pro-Vietnamese forces and the Khmer Rouge has
increased along the border in recent days, as is often the case
before diplomatic events and peace talks.
   The Khmer Rouge and the other guerrilla groups are to hold talks
with the Vietnam-installed government in Paris next week, and
attend an international conference on Cambodia starting July 30.
   Vietnam invaded Cambodia in 1978 and toppled the Khmer Rouge
government, which had killed hundreds of thousands of Cambodians in
execution chambers and slave labor camps after coming to power in
1975.
</TEXT>
