<FILEID>AP-NR-07-22-89 0501EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Brazil-Highway     07-22 0329</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Brazil-Highway,0337</SECOND>
<HEAD>Brazil Gets Money to Pave Road in Amazon</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JORGE MEDEROS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BRASILIA, Brazil (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A development bank has agreed to loan
Brazil money to begin paving a highway in the western Amazon,
ending a two-year delay caused by environmentalists worried about
the road's effect on the fragile forest.
   William Ellis, the Inter-American Development Bank's
representative in Brazil, said Friday the bank would finance 40
percent of the $146 million needed to complete the jungle project.
   Brazil will receive 80 percent of the money immediately, and the
remainder will be released after the government complies with a
promise to create Indian and forest reserves and control forest
burning in the region, Ellis said.
   At a presidential palace ceremony Thursday, Planning Minister
Joao Batista de Abreu hailed the highway as a ``salvation'' for the
remote Amazon state of Acre, which borders Peru and Bolivia about
2,657 miles northwest of Rio de Janeiro.
   Work on the highway was suspended in October 1987. When
completed, the 312-mile route would link Rio Branco, the capital of
Acre, and Porto Velho, the capital Rondonia.
   The bank, which financed the paving of 186 miles of dirt road
between the two capitals, cut off the money under pressure from
international environmental groups and the U.S. government because
of widespread cutting and burning of the tropical rainforest.
   It later demanded the government take measures to protect the
rainforest and the estimated 16,000 Indians that live in the region.
   The states of Acre and Rondonia have been devastated at an
increasing rate by landless peasants, miners and ranchers who slash
and burn the tropical rainforest and settle there.
   Environmentalists warn an asphalt roadway would spur an influx
of settlers, and lead to greater ecological destruction and
disruption of Indian communities.
   But state authorities in Acre _ the nations' poorest and most
underdeveloped state _ see the highway as the only way to break the
state's isolation from the rest of the country.
</TEXT>
