<FILEID>AP-NR-07-22-89 0451EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-Lebanon     07-22 0748</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lebanon,0774</SECOND>
<HEAD>Six Killed in Beirut Following Night-Long Shelling</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MOHAMMED SALAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Syrian and Christian forces pounded each
other's sectors with heavy shelling during the night, killing six
people and wounding more than 50 in one of the most ferocious
battles of the current conflict, police said.
   The blasts of exploding rockets and shells shook Beirut's Moslem
and Christian sectors and local radio stations interrupted regular
programming to urge civilians to rush to underground shelters.
   Police said 52 people were wounded and at least six killed in
the nine-hour battle with howitzers, rockets and tank cannons in
Beirut and the surrounding mountains.
   The 18-week confrontation between Gen. Michel Aoun's mainly
Christian troops and Syrian forces has claimed 440 lives and
wounded 1,836 people, by police count.
   Police said the right-wing Christian Lebanese Forces militia,
Aoun's ally in the confrontation with the Syrians, fired its 122mm
rocket launchers against residential districts in Moslem west
Beirut.
   ``Thousands of rockets and shells rained on Beirut last night,''
said a police spokesman, who cannot be named in line with
regulations.
   Exploding rockets ripped into hundreds of apartments, shops and
office buildings and fires blazed out of control due to lack of
water for fire engines.
   Telephone lines were out because of a total power outage in the
shattered Lebanese capital.
   ``Several casualties remained under the rubble for quite a long
time, simply because no one had a telephone line to request help
from rescuers,'' the police spokesman said.
   The civil defense directorate sent teams to tour the
debris-covered streets of west Beirut during short lulls,
announcing their presence through loudspeakers.
   ``A civil defense team is in the area. Please notify us of your
need for help,'' rescuers shouted as their ambulance drove slowly
through the Zaidaniyeh district.
   ``Over here. Over here,'' someone shouted back from the rubble
of a two-story house$
   Rockets fired from Christian east Beirut scored at least 10
direct hits on the plush, 12-story Taljeh apartment building in
west Beirut's Karakon district, inhabited by Druse Moslems,
damaging it heavily.
   ``This is not an army barracks, or an artillery emplacement.
This is a residential building. I wonder why did they do this to
us,'' said a man who identified as Abu Hassan.
   ``We were all in the underground basement, luckily,'' he said.
``All the tenants of this buildings lost their apartments,'' he
added.
   Two rockets also blasted the Samir Taxi company in west Beirut's
Zarif district, destroying the owner's four cars and a nearby
butcher's shop.
   ``I've managed to keep the company running despite 14 years of
civil war. Now I've lost the office and the cars,'' said the owner,
Abu Samir.
   The owner's oldest son was caught in the cross-fire of a clash
between rival gunmen near the taxi office and killed in the early
days of the civil war.
   ``The war took Samir and the company I named after him,'' the
white-haired Abu Samir said, his eyes brimming with tears.
   A spokesman for Aoun's command, speaking on condition he not be
named, said his gunners blasted Syrian artillery emplacements along
west Beirut's sea front and in wooded mountains south and east of
the capital.
   ``We did not direct our fire against civilians,'' said the
spokesman. He refused to elaborate.
   He accused the Syrians of provoking the barrage by shelling the
Christian-controlled coast north of Beirut Friday evening. ``We
responded to the Syrian barrage and they responded by shelling
(Christian) population centers.''
   Rockets fired by Syrian gunners started several fires in east
Beirut's Ashrafiyeh residential district and the summer resorts of
Brummana and Beit Meri, the police spokesman said.
   The overnight duel was one of the fiercest in the present round
of violence that broke out March 8. The police spokesman said
thousands of panicky civilians left Beirut during the early morning
lull heading to rural areas in the south, east and the north.
   The intensified shelling duels followed a statement by Aoun's
three-man Christian cabinet saying the only settlement to Lebanon's
crisis was ``the withdrawal of the Syrian army.''
   The Christian cabinet is vying for power with Salim Hoss' Moslem
cabinet in west Beirut.
   Aoun, 54, a Maronite Catholic, on March 8 declared a ``war of
liberation'' against Syria's 40,000 troops deployed in
predominantly Moslem sections under a 1976 peacekeeping mandate
from the 22-nation Arab League.
   The Syrians and allied Moslem Lebanese factions retaliated by
besieging the 310-square-mile Christian enclave where Aoun's troops
and the Lebanese Forces militia are entrenched.
</TEXT>
