<FIRST>r i PM-Soviet-Unrest     07-22 0468</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Soviet-Unrest,0486</SECOND>
<HEAD>Two Police Cadets Killed in Continued Unrest</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANN IMSE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TBILISI, U.S.S.R. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Assailants attacked a patrol that was
clearing roadblocks and confiscating weapons in western Georgia,
killing two police cadets in the latest bloodshed in the volatile
region, Tass said today.
   The official news agency said the attack took place Friday night
in the village of Ostapi in Abkhazia, the Black Sea resort area
where the native Abkhazians have been fighting ethnic Georgians
since July 15.
   Abkhazians are a minority in their homeland, a so-called
autonomous republic inside the republic of Georgia. Both ethnic
groups in the enclave each claim discrimination by the other.
   The patrol was clearing roadblocks set up by villagers and
confiscating weapons when it ``was fired on by unknown people using
hunting rifles,'' Tass said. Two students of a Leningrad Interior
Ministry academy, which trains police, were killed, raising the
death toll in the Abkhazian violence to 19.
   In another village, Lindava, police found a pit amid bushes
containing 374 pounds of explosives and 550 fuses with detonators,
Tass said. It said the situation in the region was not improving,
adding that public transport remained idle, many businesses
remained closed and railroad workers were still on strike.
   Radio Moscow warned that ``heaps of garbage in hot weather could
result in an epidemic.''
   Zarya Vostoka, a newspaper published in the Georgian capital
Tbilisi, said cargo trucks were getting through only when escorted
by police.
   The youth newspaper Komsomolskaya Pravda reported that someone
had freed 174 prisoners from a jail in the city of Zugdidi. It did
not give the nationality of the prisoners.
   On Tuesday, authorities declared area around Sukhumi, the
Abkhazian capital, off-limits to the millions of tourists who
vacation there each year and imposed emergency regulations,
including an 11 p.m.-to-6 a.m. curfew. Police and soldiers have
seized more than 2,700 firearms since the emergency was declared.
   Police confiscated four anti-tank and two anti-personnel mines
at one village, Zarya Vostoka said.
   ``Vremya,'' the nightly television news program, said, ``In the
last 24 hours, groups of hooligans in western Georgia have seized
almost 1,400 hunting and combat weapons'' in more than 40 raids.
   Abkhazia, 800 miles south of Moscow, remained closed to Western
reporters.
   Special flights and ships continued evacuating the thousands of
tourists stranded in Sukhumi, the Red Army newspaper Krasnaya
Zvezda reported today.
   It said 4,300 people were evacuated on 46 special flights and
15,000 were taken from Sukhumi harbor by cruise ships.
   Zarya Vostoka said 31 policemen and internal security troopers
were among the injured. The radio said the trouble was caused by
Abkhazian demands for secession from Georgia.
   At least 132 people have died in ethnic unrest during the past
month in the southern Soviet republics of Georgia, Azerbaijan,
Kazakhstan, Uzbekistan and Tadzhikistan.
</TEXT>
