<FIRST>r i PM-BRF--OldWines     07-22 0171</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-BRF--Old Wines,0173</SECOND>
<HEAD>Wines From Czar's Winery to be Sold in March</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 13,000 bottles of wine from the Crimean
winery that once belonged to the Russian czars will be auctioned in
March, Sotheby's says.
   The dessert and fortified wines include 1,155 bottles of
extremely rare pre-1918 wines, some still bearing the imperial
seal, the auction house said in a statement on Friday. All the
wines were bottled before 1945.
   ``Crimea was among the greatest producers of the classic sweet
wines that were so sought-after in the 19th century and which are
becoming fashionable again today,'' said Sotheby's.
   ``They have the greatest longevity of any wines, and are still
very drinkable now after 100 or even 150 years,'' said the auction
house, which said it expects the wines to sell for as much as
several hundred dollars a bottle.
   Sotheby's said the wines from the former imperial winery, called
Massandra, have rarely been tasted outside the Soviet Union. The
winery still is in operation, it said.
</TEXT>
