<FIRST>r i PM-HongKong-China     07-22 0277</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Hong Kong-China,0284</SECOND>
<HEAD>Thousands Flock To Exhibit on Pro-Democracy Movement</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-China</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HONG KONG (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grandparents with toddlers, parents with babies
and thousands of others crowded today into a photo exhibition
dedicated to the pro-democracy movement in China that was crushed
by troops last month.
   Titled ``Awakening,'' the photo exhibition at the Arts Center
depicted events in Beijing from the death in April of former
Communist Party chief Hu Yaobang to the student movement and
military crackdown on June 3-4.
   It included several huge color pictures of students fasting as
well as the well-known picture of a lone man standing defiantly in
front of a line of tanks.
   The exhibition also included a letter from soldiers supporting
the students, and pictures of Chinese leaders condemning the
pro-democracy movement as social turmoil.
   Many visitors crowded over an old newspaper page which showed
the bloody remains of a body crushed by a tank.
   A 10-minute multi-screen slide show accompanied by songs heard
during the movement, including the Internationale, began with the
causalities on Changan Boulevard in Beijing on June 3-4.
   It ended with a student yelling ``Freedom! Freedom!'' in front
of a row of soldiers in Beijing. The voice was drowned in a volley
of gunshot.
   An organizer of the exhibition, Peter Yung, said: ``We think the
stage of action (marches) is over. We need to educate the public.
We hope to set up a fund to help people conduct research and
studies in the democracy movement and then publish some books.''
   ``The stage of mourning is over. We need to go back to our
position and calmly review the situation,'' Yung said.
   The exhibition ends Thursday.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
