<FILEID>AP-NR-07-22-89 0621EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-DC-10Crash-Counseling     07-22 0452</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-DC-10 Crash-Counseling,0466</SECOND>
<HEAD>Survivors Receive Counseling To Cope With Crash</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-DC-10 Crash,Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRIAN STEFFEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SIOUX CITY, Iowa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Clergy and psychologists are counseling
the survivors of the United Airlines crash, many of whom are
beginning to suffer guilt over failing to save those who died.
   At Marian Health Center, where 29 victims from United Airlines
Flight 232 were hospitalized, mental health director Marcene Moran
said she and her three-member staff spent Friday talking with
survivors and emergency workers who responded to the disaster.
   ``The crash is really starting to bother them because of some of
the things they've seen and the crisis behavior they've had to
exhibit to get through this,'' she said.
   Pilot Al Haynes and his DC-10 crew were among the patients at
the hospital. They are ``feeling a great deal of sadness'' at not
having brought the plane down safely.
   ``They feel responsible,'' said Ms. Moran. Haynes is credited
with saving many lives by getting the jet to the edge of a runway
at Sioux Gateway Airport before crashing. ``We're trying to help
them reach the mind set that they did all they could in the given
set of circumstances,'' she said.
   Ms. Moran said some patients have blotted the wreck out of their
memories. In others, initial relief at survival has given way to
guilt and anger.
   ``Some of them are upset that they ran from the plane,'' she
said. ``One gentleman was angry that he went back but only helped
one person out when he thought he could have gotten more.''
   Ms. Moran said she has advised all of the survivors to seek
psychological counseling when they get home.
   Many emergency workers at first claim to be suffering no
emotional trauma, but counseling brings out upset, she said.
   ``They've come face to face with a kind of tragedy that most
people never deal with,'' she said. ``It always brings you to
confront your own possible death.''
   The Rev. Mark Duchaine, a Roman Catholic priest who has attended
to the injured and sought to comfort relatives and friends, says he
can't wipe the scene of the crash from his mind.
   ``The carnage at the airport was just unbelievable,'' Duchaine
said.
   ``Out there at the airport walking amidst the bodies and the
debris that just seemed to have disintegrated into millions of
pieces, it was like Dante's Inferno. I'll never forget it.''
   Following the wreck, Duchaine went immediately to the airport
runway, stopping at each body he found to kneel and offer last
rites. Since, he has worked with the living.
   ``When you're with these families and they're hurting, you wish
you could take some of that hurt upon yourself,'' said Duchaine.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
