<FIRST>r i PM-Italy     07-22 0264</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Italy,0272</SECOND>
<HEAD>Parties Give Green Light to Form New Government</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Political leaders gave the green light to formation
of Italy's 49th postwar government, a coalition to be led by
five-time premier Giulio Andreotti.
   Andreotti was expected to form the government today, presenting
a list of Cabinet ministers to President Francesco Cossiga. The
coalition would succeed one led by Christian Democrat Premier
Ciriaco De Mita that fell two months ago.
   Leaders of the five parties that have governed in a coalition in
recent years met with Andreotti Friday and approved his proposed
program.
   ``After this evening's meeting, the crisis can be considered
definitely resolved,'' Socialist Party leader Bettino Craxi told
reporters after the three-hour session.
   No major changes in policy were expected.
   The last government fell when Craxi criticized De Mita's
leadership shortly before the European Parliament elections. Most
observers said Craxi expected his party to make electoral gains and
wanted to be able to parlay them into a stronger position in
government. However, the Socialists recorded only a slight increase.
   The Socialists are the second-largest party in the government
after the dominant Christian Democrats. Also in the coalition are
the small Republican, Liberal and Social Democrat parties.
   Italy's second-largest party, the Communists, have been kept out
of government for four decades.
   Andreotti, a Christian Democrat, was asked to form a government
two weeks ago after De Mita failed to revive the 13-month-old
coalition that collapsed on May 19.
   Andreotti, who served as foreign minister in the De Mita
government, was premier twice in 1972-73 and three times
successively in 1976-79.
</TEXT>
