<SECOND>PM-Afghanistan,0189</SECOND>
<HEAD>Thirty-One Killed In Rocket Attack</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KABUL, Afghanistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Moslem rebels fired seven rockets into
a crowded bus terminal and near government offices today, killing
at least 31 people and injuring 80, government and hospital
officials said.
   Witnesses said one rocket struck about 100 yards from the office
of Prime Minister Ali Kishtmand and another hit about 50 yards from
the Foreign Ministry compound. Several windows were shattered by
the impact, they said.
   The government closed the area around all ministry buildings.
   ``This is a very serious attack,'' said Foreign Ministry
spokesman Mohammad Nabi Amani. He had no breakdown of casualties,
saying the government was waiting for more information.
   Witnesses said most of the victims were at a bus terminal near
the city's center.
   ``It is one of the worst rocket attacks in recent months,'' said
Sarwar Wisil, chief ot Jamhuriat Hospial, where at least 57 people
were admitted, many in critical condition.
   The guerrillas, backed by the United States and based in
neighboring Pakistan and Iran, have been fighting for 11 years to
overthrow the Soviet-supported government of President Najib.
