<FIRST>r a PM-ExxonValdez     07-22 0308</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Exxon Valdez,0316</SECOND>
<HEAD>Divers Cut Steel Plates From Valdez Hull</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN DIEGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Divers removed six of the seven steel plates
dangling from the Exxon Valdez's hull that had kept the damaged oil
tanker from entering port for repairs.
   Representatives of Exxon and the state of California met Friday
to settle environmental conditions the company must meet before
bringing the ship through San Diego Bay to the National Steel and
Shipbuilding Co. yard.
   The state wants guarantees from Exxon that the leak-prone Valdez
will make a pollution-free passage through state waters, which
extend three miles from shore.
   ``The primary objective is to find a way to get the ship
repaired while protecting the resources of the state,'' said
Anthony Summers, a deputy attorney general.
   The Valdez was about 54 miles off San Diego near San Clemente
Island, where interim repairs were being carried out to allow the
tanker to navigate the shallows of San Diego Harbor.
   Exxon Shipping Co. spokeswoman Jan Cool said the divers
inspected the ship's bottom Thursday night and found a seventh
steel plate had peeled away from the frame. Six of the plates had
been removed Friday.
   The Valdez's hull ruptured on rocks in Alaska's Prince William
Sound on March 24, spilling some 11 million gallons of crude in the
nation's worst oil spill.
   The ship received a two-month scrubbing before being towed to
the San Diego area, where it is to undergo a nine-month, $25
million repair.
   Coast Guard officials suspended the Valdez' scheduled harbor
entry on July 10, when an 18-mile oil slick was sighted near the
ship and an underwater inspection revealed the dangling plates.
   A Coast Guard observer aboard the ship had reported no signs of
discharge during four days, but reported a brown substance about 20
yards in diameter floating 50 yards from the Valdez on Friday.
</TEXT>
