<FILEID>AP-NR-07-22-89 0707EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-SovietVisit     07-22 0299</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Soviet Visit,0305</SECOND>
<HEAD>Weekend Fun Planned For Soviet Sailors</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEAN McNAIR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NORFOLK, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soviet sailors visiting the Norfolk Naval
Base were getting a taste of American life over the weekend _
shopping, eating burgers and pizza, and visiting a theme park.
   About 1,100 sailors aboard three Soviet warships arrived at the
world's largest naval base Friday. The only other post-World War II
visit by Soviet ships came in 1975 when two vessels stopped in
Boston.
   ``Our visit is taking place at a significant time,'' Vice Adm.
Igor V. Kasatonov, commander of the Soviet ships, said at a news
conference. ``New political thinking, the priority of general human
values, the course towards cooperation in solving global problems
are ever increasingly determining the world politics today.''
   Kasatonov said the Soviet Union was looking forward to regular
visits between the navies of the two superpowers. Three American
warships will stop in the Soviet Black Sea port of Sevastopol next
month.
   The public will be invited aboard two of the Soviet ships _ the
guided missile cruiser Marshal Ustinov and the destroyer Otlichny.
The tanker Gasanov will not be open to the public.
   The sailors' agenda includes bus trips to the Busch Gardens
amusement park in Williamsburg, meals at a pizza parlor and a
McDonald's restaurant, shopping at a Virginia Beach mall, a grocery
store and hardware shop.
   ``I want to know what Americans are interested in today, how
they live, how they feel about disarmament,'' said Oleg Ivanov, 20,
a sailor aboard the Ustinov. ``It will assist in our reapproachment
and we will be able to trust each other.''
   ``We have an opportunity to be witnesses of a very great event
in relations between our two countries,'' said Alexander Kabanov, a
22-year-old sailor of Moscow.
</TEXT>
