<FILEID>AP-NR-07-22-89 0748EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Israel     07-22 0616</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Israel,0635</SECOND>
<HEAD>Schools Reopen for 200,000 Arab Children in West Bank</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EILEEN ALT POWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BETHLEHEM, Occupied West Bank (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The chants of Palestinian
children reciting Arabic and practicing multiplication tables rang
out today from schools in the West Bank that were reopened after a
seven-month army closure.
   ``I'm glad to be going back,'' said 9-year-old Lina Humseyeh as
she waited for a school bus to take her to her third-grade class.
``I helped my mother when we didn't have school, but I was bored.''
   The nearly 1,200 primary and secondary schools in the occupied
West Bank have been closed for most of the 19-month Palestinian
uprising, despite appeals from the United States and international
human rights organizations.
   The Israeli government contends that the schools are hotbeds of
violence. Twice before _ in May and December of last year _ the
army reopened and then closed schools, claiming students were
inciting the uprising.
   The schools that opened today are for 200,000 children in grades
one through six and for students in their senior year of high
school, the latter so they can study for mandatory graduation exams.
   No major incidents were reported today. In several West Bank
cities, more troops than normal were seen on main roads.
   Arab reports said curfews imposed on four villages and a refugee
camp near Nablus and Ramallah blocked students from going to
school. Three Palestinians were reported wounded in clashes with
soldiers near Nablus and in Gaza City.
   The army confirmed that one Palestinian was shot and wounded in
the Nur Shams refugee camp outside Nablus and said it was checking
the other reports.
   Throughout the West Bank and Gaza Strip, shops and businesses
were closed by a general strike ordered by the Moslem
fundamentalist movement Hamas, or Zeal. The strike did not affect
the first day of school because Hamas announced in a leaflet that
it favored children returning to class.
   Graffiti on a wall outside the United Nations-run school in the
Al-Amri refugee camp near Ramallah also called on students to
pursue their eductions.
   ``With stones and pens, the blessed uprising continues,'' read
one slogan, signed by Hamas.
   Before allowing classes to resume, army officials met with
school administrators and told them they would have to control
their students or the schools would be closed again.
   Samira Abdullah Mahmoud, principal of the Bethlehem Girls
School, said that Israeli soldiers, who previously parked jeeps
across from her elementary school, today stayed 50 yards away in an
apparent effort to reduce tensions.
   ``The children become nervous when they see soldiers outside,''
she said.
   She described the school's 404 elementary schoolgirls as
``obviously happy to be back.'' To make up for the lost school
time, she said, the girls will focus on Arabic, mathematics and
science. Electives such as physical education, music and art will
not be taught.
   ``We can't do physical education anyway,'' Mrs. Mahmoud said.
``During the closure, the soldiers tore down the wall around the
playground.''
   Residents in the area said that stones, the main weapon of the
uprising, had been hurled at passing army jeeps from behind the
wall.
   No date has been set for a resumption of classes for the
remaining 100,000 West Bank students in grades seven, eight, nine,
10 and 11. The army said that would depend on whether the initial
phase of reopenings was peaceful.
   While the army ordered schools closed in the West Bank shortly
after the start of the uprising in December 1987, classes have
continued for more than 150,000 students in the Gaza Strip.
   Colleges, universities and vocational schools in both
territories remain shut, affecting 20,000 students. No date for
reopening them has been set.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
