<SECOND>PM-Boy Pilot, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0475,0312</SECOND>
<HEAD>Boy Pilot Sets Stage for Completion of World Tour</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 8th graf, `Tony and' to CORRECT Gorbachev's title.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONNA DE LA CRUZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Preparing for the last leg of his round-the-world
journey, 11-year-old pilot Tony Aliengena said when he gets home he
wants to ride his bike for a while ``and then I'd like to meet
President Bush, maybe.''
   The fourth-grader was to become the youngest person to fly a
plane around the world when he completed a 1,000-mile flight to
Orange County, Calif., today. He flew into Seattle on Friday in a
borrowed single-engine plane from Juneau, Alaska.
   Tony, who lives in San Juan Capistrano, Calif., left seven weeks
ago from nearby John Wayne International Airport on ``Friendship
Flight '89.''
   He is flying a borrowed plane because the single-engine Cessna
Centurion he started with crashed Tuesday while taking off from
Golovin, Alaska. Tony's flight-instructor father, Gary Aliengena,
was at the controls, and no one was seriously hurt.
   That crash, which is under investigation by the Federal Aviation
Administration because there were eight people aboard the six-seat
plane, was the only sour note on the 19,000-mile trip, Tony said
Friday night.
   Looking back on the 35 stops he made in seven countries, the boy
said he enjoyed himself.
   ``I really liked the Soviet Union, especially Moscow,'' he said.
``I also liked Boston because that's where all my relatives are.''
   Tony and his party, including his mother, Susan, and 10-year-old
sister Alaina, made 14 stops in the Soviet Union alone. In Moscow,
the Friendship Flight crew met with Soviet President Mikhail
Gorbachev.
   The boy is to meet President Bush at the White House next week.
   Tony said aviation will always be just a hobby.
   ``I want to be an orthopedic surgeon,'' he said.
</TEXT>
