<FILEID>AP-NR-07-22-89 0822EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Britain-Chess     07-22 0488</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Britain-Chess,0504</SECOND>
<HEAD>17-Year-Old Could be Third Youngest Grandmaster in History</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID GOODMAN</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Michael Adams, a 17-year-old British chess player,
won an international competition in London and is expected to be
the third youngest player in history to be awarded a grandmaster
title.
   Adams scored seven points out of nine in the Iclicki Masters
tournament on Friday to achieve his third grandmaster performance
in less than a year. He is expected to have his new title ratified
by the International Chess Federation at its annual Congress next
month in Puerto Rico.
   British chess experts said Bobby Fischer of the United States
and the current world champion, Soviet Garri Kasparov, are the only
players to have gained chess' top honor at an earlier age. Fischer,
who held the world title from 1972 to 1975, became a grandmaster at
15. Kasparov did that at 16.
   ``To the best of my knowledge, Michael is third,'' said Malcolm
Pein, a British international master and chess writer.
   After agreeing to a draw in his final round game, Adams said he
was ``drained,'' but added: ``Things have gone very well recently.''
   ``He's extremely talented. If he can fulfill his potential he
will reach the highest echelons of world chess,'' said Jonathan
Speelman, a British grandmaster who has reached the semi-final
stage of the world championship and trains with Adams.
   Adams is registered as a high school student in Truro in
southwest England, but admits to taking increasing amounts of time
off to play in tournaments.
   He has competed in the United States and Australia and his chess
prowess netted $17,000 in prize money last year. Now he will be
eligible for the hefty appearance monies regularly offered to
grandmasters.
   Adams said he practises ``very little'' at home and prefers to
work on his game with a partner. ``You always get a lot more done
and far more objective opinions with two,'' he said.
   Away from chess, Adams likes pop music, television, traveling
abroad and meeting with friends. He also likes to surf along the
Cornish coastline.
   ``Just flat board, nothing spectacular,'' he said. ``I would
probably be on a beach in Cornwall if I wasn't playing here.''
   He was taught the moves at the age of eight by his father, a
teacher, and went on to win the British under-11 championship.
   At 12, he shot to fame when he was the only junior to hold
Kasparov to a draw during an exhibition of simultaneous chess games.
   Adams' ranking might be threatened by other juniors. Joel
Lautier, a French 15-year-old, has achieved two of the required
three grandmaster performances.
   And Judit Polgar, 13, the youngest member of a remarkable trio
of Hungarian sisters, missed her first grandmaster result at a
tournament in New York in the spring by just half a point.
   ``There are more opportunities now,'' Adams said. ``There is so
much more around for players at a younger age.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
