<FIRST>r i PM-NorthernIreland     07-22 0199</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Northern Ireland,0202</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bomb Explodes In Northern Ireland During Defusing Attempt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BELFAST, Northern Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 100-pound bomb exploded on a
bridge near the Irish border while an army expert tried to defuse
it with a remote-control robot, police said today.
   A pub across the border in the Irish Republic was damaged by the
force of the explosion Friday night, but no one was injured, said a
spokesman for the Royal Ulster Constabulary, speaking anonymously.
   The robot the expert used while trying to defuse the bomb looks
like a tiny tank and is codenamed ``wheelbarrow,'' the spokesman
said.
   Considerable damage was done to the bridge at Moybridge, near
Aughnacloy, and it will be closed, the spokesman said.
   In mainly Roman Catholic west Belfast, a bomb trap was foiled
Friday night when a soldier patrolling Andersonstown Road spotted
an electric command wire, which someone could set off some distance
away, and alerted his colleagues. Police said the wire led to a
six-pound Semtex bomb packed with nuts and bolts.
   Also Friday, two hand grenades were thrown at the perimeter
fence of a police station in Craigavon, County Armagh, but police
said they caused little damage and no injuries.
</TEXT>
