<FILEID>AP-NR-07-22-89 0839EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Namibia-Poaching     07-22 0331</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Namibia-Poaching,0340</SECOND>
<HEAD>Poaching Increases After South African Troops Leave Namibia</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WINDHOEK, Namibia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Poaching of elephants and rhinoceroses
has increased dramatically since the withdrawal of South African
army units, a police official said today.
   Chief Inspector Kierie du Rand said the territorial police force
has formed three anti-poaching units to try to fill the void
created after nearly all South African troops left earlier this
year as part of a U.N.-supervised plan to bring independence to
Namibia.
   He said the units consisted mainly of black constables who
formerly served in Koevoet, a counterinsurgency force active in the
23-year bush war against guerrillas of SWAPO, the South-West Africa
People's Organization. Many Koevoet members were expert trackers.
   Police have reported the arrest of 30 suspected poachers in the
past six weeks, but wildlife experts say stronger measures are
needed to halt the smuggling of ivory and rhino horns out of
Namibia.
   According to the South African-based Rhino and Elephant
Foundation, at least 11 black rhinos and 30 elephants have been
killed by poachers in Namibia since June. The black rhino is one of
the most endangered species of large mammals, with only about 3,500
believed to exist worldwide.
   Two months ago, Namibian conservationists began an unprecedented
experimental program to deter rhino poachers by removing the horns
of some of the animals. The horns can earn thousands of dollars for
smugglers from buyers in Asia who use them to make potions and
dagger handles.
   Some conservationists have complained that the U.N. military and
police contingents observing the independence process in Namibia
are uninterested in assisting wildlife protection programs.
   The poaching issue was among several topics discussed Friday
during talks in Pretoria between South African Foreign Minister Pik
Botha and U.N. Secretary General Javier Perez de Cuellar.
   South Africa, which took control of Namibia during World War I,
has agreed to grant independence as part of a regional peace accord
that also calls for withdrawal of Cuban troops from Angola,
Namibia's northern neighbor.
</TEXT>
