<FIRST>r a PM-Reagan-Induction     07-22 0412</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Reagan-Induction,0423</SECOND>
<HEAD>Reagan Inducted Into Cowboy Hall of Fame</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RON JENKINS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>OKLAHOMA CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ronald Reagan jokingly said he feels
``somewhat qualified'' for induction into the National Cowboy Hall
of Fame because of a much-publicized fall from a horse in Mexico on
July 4.
   On Friday, the former president was inducted into the museum's
Hall of Great Westerners _ a honor bestowed on a wide range of
Westerners ranging from pioneers to presidents to cattlemen. Reagan
also was inducted into the Western Performers Hall of Fame.
   Reagan also said during the induction ceremony that he was now a
full-fledged rancher, with a spread that's grown from eight acres
to nearly 700.
   ``I just want you to know I will always treasure this award,
even though I didn't get into as many westerns as I would have
liked,'' Reagan told the cheering gathering of 800.
   The 78-year-old Reagan, wearing a dark pin-striped suit, was in
a half-dozen Western movies, but he said he would have preferred to
have been in many more. In all, he was in 53 films.
   Reagan said he wrangled often with Jack Warner, head of Warner
Bros. studios, for a part in Westerns and once feared that if he
ever did get into a Western it would be as ``an Eastern lawyer.''
   Before entering the Western museum, nestled on Persimmon Hill
near the famed Chisolm Trail, Reagan posed for photographs in front
of a ``calvary re-enactment group'' from the nearby town of Guthrie
and a group of mock U.S. marshals.
   Two volleys from a cannon welcomed the former president to his
first visit to the national Western shrine.
   William Arrington of Pampa, Texas, president of the hall's board
of directors, presented Reagan with a bronze replica of the Charles
M. Russell statue ``The Wrangler,'' in recognition of his induction
into the Hall of Western Performers.
   Reagan is the first performer to be honored since Dale Robertson
and Kirk Douglas were inducted in 1984. Others inductees include
such Western film stars as Tom Mix, Gary Cooper, Gene Autry, Walter
Brennan, Roy Rogers, Dale Evans and Jimmy Stewart.
   Western films Reagan appeared in included ``Santa Fe Trail,''
``Law and Order,'' ``Tennessee Partner,'' and ``Cattle Queen of
Montana,'' with Barbara Stanwyck, who also has been inducted.
   Reagan also received a bronze medallion in recognition of his
induction into the Hall of Great Westerners, a group that also
includes Presidents Abraham Lincoln, Teddy Roosevelt and Dwight
Eisenhower.
</TEXT>
