<FILEID>AP-NR-07-22-89 0915EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-Soviet-Strikes 2ndLd-Writethru a0466 07-22 0690</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Soviet-Strikes, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0466,0711</SECOND>
<HEAD>Coal Minister Jawbones Miners in Ukraine</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos MOSB1, MOSB2</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANDREW KATELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Some Ukrainian coal miners reportedly returned to
the pits as the nation's coal minister tried today to end their
crippling strike, but hundreds of thousands of miners elsewhere
ignored the official appeals.
   The strikes, the country's worst labor unrest in six decades,
began July 11. Fuel was reportedly running out at vital Soviet
industries, and President Mikhail Gorbachev has called for
replacing party officials whom he accused of taking a ``passive,
waiting position'' on economic reforms.
   A receptionist at the Communist Party office in the eastern
Ukraine city of Donetsk said the coal minister, Mikhail I.
Shchadov, today spoke to a rally of 3,000 miners in the central
square.
   The receptionist, interviewed by phone, said she had no details
of his remarks, but there were indications the miners were
receiving him well.
   About 300,000 miners in the area, the Donetsk Basin, have been
striking since July 15. They have held out for more concessions
than those granted to Siberian miners who began the strikes July 11
but returned to work earlier this week. They gained pay increases,
pledges of more consumer goods and greater control over their
industry.
   The newspaper Sovietskaya Rossiya today reported the number of
striking mines in Donetsk fell to 70 from 94 on Friday. The region
has 121 mines.
   The Donetsk Basin contains the country's largest coal field.
   But the paper and the labor daily Trud said miners remained off
the job at all 26 mines in the Karaganda Basin of the southern
republic of Kazakhstan, at 11 of 13 mines in Vorkuta in the Pechora
Basin in the Arctic, and at all 12 mines in Chervonograd in the
western Ukraine.
   The reports indicated half the coal industry's 1 million workers
were involved in the walkout.
   Among their demands, the Donetsk miners want 45 days of vacation
a year, rather than the 42 granted to Siberian miners, Trud said,
quoting a strike leader identified as V. Koval.
   The Karaganda miners are demanding, among other things, that
nuclear weapons tests be stopped at the Semipalatinsk range in
Kazakhstan and that destruction of medium-range nuclear weapons be
stopped elsewhere in the republic, according to Trud. The miners
say these activities harm the environment.
   In the face of the growing unrest, Communist Party leaders have
bemoaned what they called ideological confusion in the party under
reforms. In speeches published Friday by the party newspaper
Pravda, the leaders said party activists were hampered by
opposition forces unleashed by the reforms. They called for tight
restrictions on the press and a clear second-in-command.
   Gorbachev, who assumed power in 1985, has encouraged more open
debate as part of his efforts to restructure Soviet society and the
economy. Ethnic groups and workers, however, have used the climate
of greater openness to put forth long-simmering demands.
   Gorbachev, in a speech to party leaders on Tuesday, said some
party officials had taken a ``passive, waiting position'' and
longed for a return to ``good times'' to avoid making the difficult
decisions required to improve the country. These officials _
including some of those at the very top in the Politburo _ must be
replaced, he said without naming names.
   The economic toll and threat to the coke and steel industries
were a major theme of today's press reports. Coke is a coal
derivative also used as a fuel.
   Sovietskaya Rossiya said the steel industry was in a ``critical
state'' because it lacked coal.
   A Karaganda steel plant director said he had only a day's worth
of coal reserves, and steelworkers in Pavlograd in the Donetsk
Basin said they had only a two-day supply, newspapers reported.
   Pravda said a boiler station and an asphalt plant in Pavlograd
have shut down because of the fuel shortage.
   Trud said the Kuznetsk strike has blocked production of $103
million worth of coal.
   The strikes coincided with nationalist violence that has nearly
paralyzed western Soviet Georgia. Tass said today that assailants
on Friday attacked a patrol that was clearing roadblocks in the
region, killing two police cadets.
</TEXT>
