<FILEID>AP-NR-07-22-89 0923EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Japan-Supercomputers     07-22 0272</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Japan-Supercomputers,0280</SECOND>
<HEAD>Press Reports say Hitachi, Cray to Exchange Technology on Supercomputers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cray Research Inc. of the United States, the
world's largest supercomputer maker, and Hitachi, Ltd. have agreed
to share technology in Cray's first deal with a Japanese computer
maker, media reports said today.
   Hitachi and Cray officials were not immediately available for
comment.
   The nationally circulated Asahi Shimbun newspaper, Japan
Broadcasting Corp., and Kyodo News Service, all quoting
unidentified ``industry sources,'' said the two have agreed to
exchange supercomputer hardware technology, including circuits for
high-speed analysis of scientific information.
   New technology as yet to be patented by either company as well
as existing technology will be shared, the reports said.
   Kyodo News Service reported the agreement will enable Hitachi to
obtain technology from Cray, which has more experience than Hitachi
in supercomputers, and will allow Hitachi, which has never sold
supercomputers overseas, to step into the U.S. and European
supercomputer markets.
   The deal also helps Hitachi avoid patent troubles with the
Minneapolis-based Cray, Asahi reported.
   Meanwhile, the agreement will give Cray access to Japanese
technology and help it expand sales in Japan by using Hitachi's
marketing network, Kyodo said.
   The Nihon Keizai Shimbun, a daily business newspaper, reported
today that Hitachi also made an agreement with Hewlett-Packard Co.,
based in Palo Alto, Calif., to share technology to produce
sophisticated computer work stations.
   News reports say Hitachi's deals with Cray may ease trade
friction with the United States, which under the Super 301 clause
of a new U.S. trade law cited supercomputer trade as one area in
which Japan maintains unfair trade practices that exclude American
products.
</TEXT>
