<FIRST>r i AM-Brazil-AIDS     07-22 0217</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Brazil-AIDS,0224</SECOND>
<HEAD>Brazil Launches AIDS Prevention Campaign ^Eds: One name only for
Zico is cq</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRASILIA, Brazil (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government is launching a new
television campaign this week to try to stem the spread of AIDS,
which has killed more than 3,500 people in this country.
   With 7,182 cases registered between 1980 and last June, Brazil
trails only the United States and France in the number of confirmed
AIDS cases, according to Dr. Lair Guerra da Macedo, director of the
National Division of Sexually Transmitted Diseases.
   The ``Project AIDS'' campaign will begin Wednesday with a series
of nationwide broadcasts by 18 well-known musicians, athletes, TV
personalities, and artists talking about the risks of acquired
immune deficiency syndrome, the Health Ministry said.
   ``We can't lose this contest,'' says Zico, a 36-year-old soccer
star, in one of the TV spots.
   Among other personalities appearing in the spots are singer
Caetano Veloso, racing champion Ayrton Senna, and artist Ivo
Pitanguy.
   The Health Ministry has said the number of AIDS sufferers in
Brazil could rise to 38,000 by 1993.
   AIDS attacks the body's immune system, leaving victims
susceptible to infections and cancers.
   It is spread most often through sexual contact, needles or
syringes shared by drug abusers, infected blood or blood products,
and from pregnant women to their offspring.
</TEXT>
