<FILEID>AP-NR-07-22-89 1048EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Japan-Farmers     07-22 0588</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan-Farmers,0603</SECOND>
<HEAD>Angry Farmers Turning Their Backs on Ruling Party</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Japan-Election, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TETSUO JIMBO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   On top of its troubles with sex and money scandals
and an unpopular new tax, the governing party goes into
parliamentary elections Sunday facing a loss of support from some
traditional backers _ the nation's farmers.
   Farm groups see the government as too weak in its stance against
U.S. demands for a wider opening of Japan's market to American
beef, oranges and other products. They fear the next step could be
an end to Japan's near ban on imports of rice, the nation's staple
food.
   For the governing Liberal Democratic Party, loss of farm support
comes at a bad time. Media polls indicate it faces serious setbacks
because of the 4-month-old sales tax, a widespread
influence-peddling scandal, and allegations that Prime Minister
Sousuke Uno kept paid mistresses.
   Because of the arrangement of Japan's electoral districts, a
rural vote is calculated as weighing up to six times as much as an
urban vote in Sunday's election for half the seats in Parliament's
upper house.
   ``It is the first election since the formation of the Liberal
Democratic Party (in 1955) that farmers, who have always been loyal
to the ruling party, so loudly expressed opposition to the LDP,''
said Takayoshi Miyagawa, president of Seiji Koho Center, a
prominent research firm.
   In the past, he said, farmers' opposition to certain policies
has not translated into votes for the opposition.
   Last month, however, a Socialist Party homemaker defeated an LDP
candidate in an upper house by-election in Niigata prefecture,
Japan's largest rice-growing district.
   ``Without the farmers' rebellion against the LDP, the Socialist
candidate couldn't have won in Niigata, which is traditionally a
conservative stronghold,'' said Masumi Ishikawa, a political
commentator for the national newspaper Asahi Shimbun.
   Like many other Japanese, he added, farmers were unhappy with
the 3 percent sales tax that took effect in April, making their
fertilizer and farm equipment more expensive.
   What angered farmers most, however, was the government's timid
attitude toward U.S. demands to open Japan's agricultural markets
wider, said Yasushi Akiba, an official at Agricultural Cooperatives
in Yamagata, in northern Japan.
   Japan, already the best foreign customer for American farmers,
has agreed to remove quotas on imported beef and oranges in 1991.
It also opened its market to 10 other farm products after an
international trade body upheld a U.S. complaint.
   ``Japanese farming is not yet competitive enough to stand
against foreign products,'' said Tokuo Matsumoto, executive
director of the Central Union of Agricultural Cooperatives, the
most powerful farm lobby. ``Simply exposing Japan's agriculture to
foreign competition at this point will permanently jeopardize this
country's agriculture.''
   The cooperatives' prefectural organ in Yamagata has decided not
to support the local LDP candidate.
   ``There is a sense of crisis mounting among farmers about the
future of Japan's agriculture,'' said Akiba. ``We have long
supported the LDP, but we can't find party policies to protect us.
We are concerned such a weak stance by the LDP may eventually
sacrifice Japan's rice market.''
   At least 17 local farm lobby groups have officially decided not
to endorse LDP candidates. Three of them are endorsing their own
candidates to run against the governing party.
   It is unclear to what extent farmers might turn to opposition
parties.
   ``Farmers are aware that the Socialists cannot necessarily
protect them either,'' said Ishikawa. ``It is yet to be seen if
they will actually go into the voting booth and write Socialist
Party members' names.''
</TEXT>
