<FIRST>r i AM-Asia-Quake     07-22 0128</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Asia-Quake,0132</SECOND>
<HEAD>Earthquake Reported Southeast of Manila</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HONG KONG (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A strong earthquake hit the Pacific Ocean
southeast of the Philippines on Saturday, but no injuries or damage
were reported, officials said.
   The quake registered 5.6 on the Richter scale, the Royal Hong
Kong Observatory reported. It placed the epicenter about 930 miles
southeast of Manila.
   A spokesman said the quake was recorded at 1:07 p.m. Hong Kong
time and that no other details were available.
   The Richter scale is a gauge of the energy released by an
earthquake as measured by ground motion recorded on a seismograph.
   Every increase of one number means that the ground motion is 10
times greater. A quake of magnitude 6 quake can cause severe damage
in a populated area.
