<FILEID>AP-NR-07-22-89 1141EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Pakistan-USPlanes     07-22 0334</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Pakistan-US Planes,0342</SECOND>
<HEAD>Report: Pakistan Can Outfit U.S. Jets With Nuclear Weapons</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HAMBURG, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pakistan has developed technology
to outfit U.S.-made F-16 fighter jets with nuclear weapons, a
report said Saturday.
   Der Spiegel magazine, quoting unidentified West German
intelligence officials, said Pakistan developed sophisticated
computer and electronic technology to make it possible for its
F-16s to carry nuclear bombs.
   Spiegel, which is based in Hamburg, said that since Pakistan
developed the technology, Washington has approved the delivery of
60 new F-16s to Pakistan. According to Spiegel, the planes
delivered to Pakistan did not contain the electronic components
needed to allow the jets to carry nuclear payloads. But the
magazine said Pakistan has since been able to develop the systems
itself.
   Pakistan has denied widespread reports it has nuclear weapons.
Its prime minister, Benazir Bhutto, offered to open Pakistan's
nuclear facilities to international inspection but only if its
traditional rival, India, does the same. India's prime minister,
Rajiv Gandhi, has refused to do so.
   Spiegel also quoted unidentified sources in Bonn as saying that
the government is upset about Washington's sale of F-16s to
Pakistan because U.S. officials have criticized similar West German
exports to other countries.
   ``They put us in the accused dock, while they go ahead and do
business,'' Spiegel quoted a government official as saying.
   A summary of Spiegel's report, which will appear in its Monday
edition, was telexed to other news media in advance.
   West Germany's export laws have been under intense criticism for
loopholes that have allegedly allowed shipments of sensitive
materials to countries with purported plans to use them for
military purposes.
   The biggest scandal occurred late last year after U.S.
allegations that West German firms were linked to a chemical
weapons production facility in Libya.
   West Germany first insisted there was no proof of the American
claims. But later, West Germany launched its own criminal
investigation that resulted in the arrest of the head of a chemical
firm on suspicion of violating export laws.
</TEXT>
