<FIRST>r i AM-Soviet-Politics     07-22 0313</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Politics,0323</SECOND>
<HEAD>Party Boss of Kiev Who Lost Election Resigns</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Communist Party boss of Kiev resigned
Saturday, four months after failing to win a seat in the new Soviet
legislature, the official Tass news agency reported.
   The resignation of Konstantin I. Masik followed a warning by
President Mikhail S. Gorbachev on Tuesday that inefficient
officials would be replaced.
   Masik was relieved as first secretary of the Kiev Communist
Party Committee ``at his own request,'' Tass said. It said he was
transferred to another position, but it did not identify Masik's
new job.
   He was replaced by A.I. Kornienko, formerly deputy head of the
city's construction and personnel department, Tass said.
   Kiev's mayor, V. Zgurski, also lost in the March 26 elections
for seats on the Congress of People's Deputies.
   Masik is the second party boss of a major city to be replaced
after losing in the elections.
   On July 12, Yuri F. Solovyov, the party boss of Leningrad and a
candidate member of the ruling Politburo, was ousted as first
secretary of the country's second-largest city.
   Gorbachev said at the time that the retirement of Solovyov was a
critical step in ``developing the process of democratization of the
internal life of the entire party.''
   In a speech to high-ranking officials of the Communist Party
Central Committee on Tuesday, Gorbachev said some party officials
had taken a ``passive, waiting position'' and longed for a return
to ``good times'' to avoid making the difficult decisions required
to improve the country. These officials _ including some of those
at the very top in the Politburo _ must be replaced, he said,
without naming names.
   Gorbachev said these officials should have expected rough times
when they initially supported perestroika, or economic and social
restructuring, because they knew it would be a revolution and ``a
revolutionary time is not a comfortable situation.''
</TEXT>
