<FILEID>AP-NR-07-22-89 1205EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-Starr     07-22 0833</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Starr,790</SECOND>
<HEAD>New Solicitor General Tired of Speculation About Getting Court Job</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD CARELLI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Kenneth W. Starr is looking forward to his
first Supreme Court argument as the federal government's
top-ranking courtroom lawyer, but he is weary of speculation that
his role in such sessions might someday be as a high court member.
   Willing to discuss _ in cautious terms _ such politically
sensitive issues as abortion and flag-burning in a recent interview
with The Associated Press, Starr drew the line at talking about a
Supreme Court nomination.
   ``I'm not going to comment at all on anything with respect to
the future. My job is right here, and I'm terribly occupied with
the here and now,'' said the former federal appellate judge who two
months ago became the Bush administration's solicitor general.
   During Senate confirmation hearings earlier this year, Starr was
asked why he would leave his appeals court seat, with its lifetime
tenure, for a job that could last just four years. He said the
Justice Department job was ``a great privilege'' he could not turn
down.
   When Sen. Arlen Specter, R-Pa., inquired whether a possible
Supreme Court nomination had been discussed, Starr said it had not.
There was ``no arrangement, no understanding of any kind whatsoever
and, indeed, no discussion of any such matter,'' Starr testified.
   But a judge's life clearly appeals to Starr, 43. ``I very much
enjoyed being a judge,'' he told The Associated Press of his five
years on the U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals in Washington. ``I was
immensely professionally satisfied with being a judge.''
   But as solicitor general Starr is a player, not a referee, eager
for the contest.
   His first Supreme Court appearance will come next fall in a case
growing out of efforts to racially desegregate Yonkers, N.Y.
   Four Yonkers city councilmen are seeking to overturn fines
imposed against them for initially defying a federal judge's order
to adopt a housing desegregation plan. The city had been sued by
the federal government.
   Starr will argue that the judge did not exceed his authority in
assessing the fines.
   ``It's a very important case which raises quite fundamental
issues,'' Starr said. ``There are certain cases that lend
themselves to being argued by the solicitor general personally.
This struck me as one in that category.''
   The fact that Starr will argue on the side supported by civil
rights activists is in stark contrast to several of the
high-profile cases argued by his predecessor, Charles Fried,
criticized by those who said he was too willing to mix litigation
with conservative politics.
   In Supreme Court appearances as solicitor general in the
administration of former President Reagan, Fried vigorously opposed
broad use of affirmative action and expansive interpretation of
civil rights law.
   Starr said he has ``the highest respect and affection for
Charles,'' and added, ``I'm not going to comment on aspects of
practice when I was not here.''
   While noting it is appropriate for White House officials to
contact him and his staff about Supreme Court cases in which
President Bush is interested, Starr said, ``I think every solicitor
general has to be prepared to follow the dictates of his
conscience, informed by his professional judgment.
   ``If he cannot in conscience subscribe to a particular legal
position, he is duty bound as an officer of the court ... not to
advance it,'' Starr said.
   Will the Bush administration seek to participate in the three
abortion rights cases to be argued before the Supreme Court when
its new term begins in October?
   ``That is uncertain,'' Starr said, adding that the final
determination will be made by Attorney General Dick Thornburgh.
``This is a unique case of obvious importance.''
   Starr refused to say whether he agrees with Thornburgh's support
for a constitutional amendment to overcome the Supreme Court's June
decision that burning the American flag is a constitutionally
protected form of political protest.
   ``I'm going to stay completely out of it. That is now in the
political arena,'' Starr said.
   Asked about his first reaction to the court's decision, Starr
said, ``It was not a surprise to me that the court would conclude
that this was symbolic speech protected under the First Amendment.
That was not a surprise.''
   A Justice Department priority under former Attorney General
Edward Meese III had been finding the appropriate case in which to
ask the Supreme Court to overturn its 1966 decision in Miranda vs.
Arizona.
   In it, the court required police to warn criminal suspects of
their right to remain silent and to have a lawyer's help before
answering any questions.
   Overturning the Miranda ruling is not a Bush administration
priority, Starr indicated.
   ``If, in fact, the law enforcement apparatus of the federal
government felt that any issue was one of concern and vexation to
them, that's something that would have to be weighed and analyzed
at that time. I simply am aware of no sense in the administration
of a call to overrule'' the Miranda decision.
</TEXT>
