<DOCNO> AP890722-0078 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-22-89 1216EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-CrashReconstruction Bjt   07-22 1265</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Crash Reconstruction, Bjt,1301</SECOND>
<HEAD>The Crash of United Flight 232: `Brace, Brace, Brace'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MITCHELL LANDSBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Looking back, it's easy to spot the little ironies. Garry Priest
had called his mother to tell her he loved her. Bill Entrup had
been turned away because the plane was overbooked.
   ``Garry never does that,'' Jeri Priest thought later, when she
heard the news about Flight 232. Bill Entrup had thought, ``Wait a
minute. That's my ticket.''
   But earlier Wednesday, when the DC-10 had thundered down the
runway at Stapleton International Airport and lifted into the clear
Denver sky, there was no reason to think twice about those things.
At that point, United Flight 232 was just another two-hour hop to
Chicago.
   Priest, a 23-year-old communications specialist for a Denver
restaurant chain, was going to Chicago on business. Mark Gearhart,
a Colorado veterinarian, was heading to Ohio for his 15th high
school reunion. Ruth Gomez of Bloomfield, N.M., was taking her
three children to visit their grandfather in Maine.
   Altogether, there were 285 or 286 passengers _ the precise
number remains in dispute _ and 11 crew members on board.
Miraculously, 186 people survived when Flight 232 ended in flames
in an Iowa cornfield. Tragically, at least 110 people died.
   Garry Priest lived; Mark Gearhart died. Paul and Leah Gomez
lived; their mother, Ruth, and brother John died.
   Experts can offer explanations for why some lived and some died.
Basically, it comes down to seat location and blind luck. But it's
doubtful that will ever mean much to Garry Priest or Paul and Leah
Gomez.
   The trouble started at 3:16 p.m. CDT.
   The flight was about 1{ hours out of Denver. Some of the
passengers were watching a sports videotape on the plane's movie
screens; others were talking, reading, sleeping.
   Suddenly there was an explosion from the rear of the plane that
knocked the flight attendants to the floor. And then, recalled
David Landsberger, a businessman from Caldwell, N.J., ``We were
going down.''
   Jerome Milford, an Indianapolis accountant returning from a
Colorado vacation, said it was ``like going on an elevator and
going down too fast. We were losing altitude, and they told us
they'd lost an engine.''
   In the cockpit, Capt. Al C. Haynes, who flew in the Korean War
and had been a United pilot for 33 years, was telling air traffic
controllers in Minneapolis that the jet had lost an engine and was
losing altitude. One minute later, he reported a ``complete
hydraulic failure'' of the jet's steering system; the Minneapolis
tower told him to take the plane to Dubuque, Iowa.
   The Federal Aviation Administration later discovered that a fan
was missing from the tail engine; it apparently had exploded,
slicing through the hydraulic steering system.
   At 3:20, Haynes declared an emergency and the flight was
rerouted to Sioux City, Iowa. Haynes told passengers that the plane
had lost an engine and would be late.
   At 3:30, some field workers were returning from a coffee break
at Alta, Iowa, 60 miles east of Sioux City, when they discovered an
8-foot by 12-foot section of the plane in a soybean-and-corn field.
They notified local authorities.
   Ten minutes after that, Haynes got on the plane's public address
system again and announced that the jet's tail section was damaged.
The flight would make an emergency landing in Sioux City, he said.
   ``He sounded a little stressed,'' Landsberger recalled. Some
passengers were beginning to get hysterical, although most remained
calm.
   ``At one point,'' recalled Jerome Milford, ``a co-pilot came
back and looked out over the wing of the plane, and he was very
concerned also. We were hoping it would just be a soft landing and
that we would walk away and think nothing of it. But that wasn't
the case.''
   Passenger Ron Rhode of Marysville, Ohio, noticed that an
8-year-old boy, Ben Radtke of Prairie View, Ill., was traveling
alone. Rhode moved to the seat next to him.
   In the cockpit, the crew was becoming desperate. ``If you've got
any ideas, we could use them,'' one crew member told ground
controllers. A pilot in another plane heard this message over his
radio: ``We need an airport, an interstate, a gravel road, a field.
We're coming down someplace.''
   As they approached Sioux City, Landsberger said, ``The plane was
rocking from side to side.'' Haynes was trying to steer the jet by
controlling the speed of his remaining wing-mounted engines. Flight
attendants told passengers to read the emergency instructions in
the seat pocket in front of them, and ran them through a practice
drill.
   ``They told us to keep our seatbelts fastened tightly and to put
our heads between our legs. About four minutes before we crashed,
they told us to brace ourselves,'' Landsberger said.
   As the plane approached for a landing at Sioux Gateway Airport,
Haynes repeated the order: ``Brace, brace, brace.''
   ``We really thought we were going to make it,'' passenger Debbie
Belliveau said.
   At 3:58, the plane skimmed toward the runway, pitched violently
to its right, scraped its right wing and cartwheeled across the
runway, exploding into flames. It landed in a cornfield, shattered
in pieces.
   ``I was peeking, if you will, and I saw us hit,'' said passenger
Charlie Martz, a private pilot from Castle Rock, Colo. ``I closed
my eyes and hoped, with a pillow over my head.
   ``We rolled upside down, and inside out and every which way. The
plane broke into three pieces, and bodies all over the place,
hanging upside down.
   ``I unfastened my belt and dropped a little ways. ... Finally I
saw what I thought was an open window, but there were flames. I
said, `To hell with it, I'm going for it' and I went through the
flames. I can't believe it, there were people with feet missing and
arms missing, it's the goddamndest thing I've ever seen in my
life.''
   Ron Rhode and another passenger, Danny Surge of Chicago, were
with young Bed Radtke. The plane ``hit and bounced, then flipped
and spun around so we ended up upside down,'' Rhode said. ``I let
go and asked Dan for the kid.''
   Surge handed Ben to Rhode, who shoved him out the plane.
   ``I thought I was going to die,'' Ben said later, still
clutching a United Airlines button and a pair of plastic pilot's
wings.
   Landsberger said that after the plane stopped sliding, ``We just
all walked out into a cornfield. I was a little dazed. I do know
that I probably stepped on some people or something as we were
walking out, but I knew if we stopped we'd all get bottled up.''
   Seven-year-old Paul Gomez had been sitting with his 10-year-old
brother, John, his 4-year-old sister, Leah, and his 35-year-old
mother, Ruth.
   After the crash, as he and Leah fled the burning plane, Paul
said he heard his brother yelling that he was stuck.
   ``Nobody would help him,'' Paul said. ``Mom tried.''
   She and John Gomez were listed among the unconfirmed dead.
   When Garry Priest stepped out of the wreckage, he said, the
runway looked ``like a war zone. Bodies, trash, magazines, luggage
and pieces of bodies littered the area. It was the worst thing I've
ever seen.''
   But the evacuation was ``real organized,'' he said. ``Everybody
was just saying, `OK folks, let's take our time. Let's just walk
out,' and we did.''
   People on the ground couldn't believe their eyes. Nobody could
walk away from a crash like that, nobody. But there they were,
bruised and burned and amazed as anybody that they could be alive.
They will always wonder why.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
