<FILEID>AP-NR-07-22-89 1224EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-SouthAfrica     07-22 0519</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-South Africa,0530</SECOND>
<HEAD>Leader of Governing Party Says ANC Should Emulate Mandela</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SAHM VENTER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SOMERSET WEST, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The leader of the governing
National Party said Saturday the African National Congress should
``follow the lead'' of Nelson Mandela by committing itself to a
peaceful settlement in South Africa.
   F.W. de Klerk, expected to succeed P.W. Botha as president after
elections in September, told a party congress he had supported the
planning of the meeting this month between Botha and Mandela, the
ANC leader who has been imprisoned since 1962 and is serving a life
term for sabotage and plotting to overthrow the government.
   The meeting, at Botha's residence in Cape Town, ``was in the
best interest of South Africa,'' de Klerk said. He made no direct
reference to the possibility of Mandela's release but implied that
the ANC leader was now considered by the government to be a
potential voice of reconciliation.
   Few details of the surprise Mandela-Botha meeting have been
disclosed beyond a statement from Justice Minister Kobie Coetsee,
who was present and said both leaders confirmed ``their support for
peaceful development'' in South Africa.
   Mandela later issued his own statement confirming the accuracy
of Coetsee's comment but emphasizing that no peaceful solution
could be found unless the government negotiated with the ANC and
its allied groups in South Africa.
   The ANC, the largest guerrilla group fighting the government, is
illegal in South Africa.
   De Klerk, in his speech to 500 National Party delegates from
Cape Province, appeared to be trying to drive a wedge between
Mandela and the ANC, which has waged a bombing and sabotage
campaign in South Africa since 1961.
   ``As a result of its relationship with Mr. Mandela, the ANC
cannot escape addressing the issue at stake: is it prepared to
follow the lead given by him and to commit itself to the pursuit of
peaceful solutions?'' de Klerk asked.
   ``The ball is now squarely in the ANC's court and not, as some
would have it, in the government's.''
   If the ANC wants to engage in dialogue, it should abandon
``violence and terrorism,'' said de Klerk, adding, ``We are not
afraid to talk to people who differ from us.''
   The National Party wants to talk to ``recognized leaders'' of
all factions, de Klerk said. ``Scientific surveys prove beyond
doubt that the support of the ANC is absolutely overrated in many
quarters.''
   De Klerk reiterated his vision of a ``new South Africa'' in
which the disenfranchised black majority would have a formal voice
in national politics but would not be able to impose its will on
the white minority.
   Earlier in the day, Botha and his wife, Elize, made an
appearance at the congress. The outgoing president received several
standing ovations and was honored by a motion praising him as ``one
of South Africa's greatest sons.''
   ``I am a happy man because I live in a country of hope, a
country of the future,'' said Botha, 73. ``All I ask is when we
make the choices when we build the future, let's hold each other
together with loyalty.''
</TEXT>
