<FILEID>AP-NR-07-22-89 1227EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-FishingWars     07-22 0544</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Fishing Wars,520</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S., Canada To Hold Talks On Fishing Border Conflicts</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CALLAHAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The State Department has invited Canadian
diplomats to a meeting here next week to resolve increasingly tense
boundary disputes between American fishermen and armed Canadian
marine patrols.
   Rep. Gerry E. Studds, D-Mass., a senior member of the House
Merchant Marine and Fisheries Committee who pushed for the
negotiations, said he fears the disputes _ with each side accusing
the other of border cheating _ will end in tragedy.
   ``If this keeps up, someone is going to get killed,'' said
Studds, a critic of the Canadians' aggressive gun-pointing pursuits
of American fishing vessels spotted on the Canadian side of Georges
Bank off the Northeast coast.
   ``Clearly we have had some U.S. fishermen who have stretched
their luck, probably knowingly,'' the congressman said in a recent
interview. ``We do not condone that. But even in those cases, we
don't believe there is an excuse for armed force the way the
Canadians are doing.''
   Edward E. Wolfe, deputy assistant secretary of state for oceans
and fisheries affairs, agrees that the current situation risks
``more serious incidents and possibly loss of life.''
   Several days after meeting with Studds, Wolfe invited officials
at the Canadian Department of Fisheries and Oceans to a series of
meetings on the growing border tensions. The meetings are scheduled
for July 31, Aug. 1 and Aug. 2.
   Wolfe, in an interview last week, said the bilateral meetings
would cover ``the whole range of legal, navigational and law
enforcement issues.''
   While the Canadians are expected to accept the invitation to
what Wolfe described as an ``urgent meeting,'' differences over the
border patrols remain deep.
   ``There's always room to maintain an open dialogue on ways in
which (the patrols) might be handled. But that's not to say there
is anything wrong at the present,'' said a Canadian Embassy
official who has followed the dispute.
   Studds, whose Cape Cod and southeastern Massachusetts district
relies heavily on commercial fishing, believes many of the border
crossings by U.S. vessels are ``honest mistakes.''
   Jeff Pike, an aide to the congressman, said five of the six
navigational charts issued to American fishermen by the National
Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration contain U.S.-Canadian border
errors of up to four miles.
   That, along with differences in readings from navigational
equipment in the two countries, can account for many of the border
crossings, Studds said.
   The Canadian government, however, maintains that the U.S.
fishermen are knowingly entering Canadian waters to get an edge in
competitive fishing markets.
   ``We certainly believe they're crossing the border
deliberately,'' said Hugh Trudeau, director of Atlantic operations
for the Canadian Department of Fisheries and Oceans.
   The disputes stem from an International Court of Justice
decision in 1984 establishing a border to separate the two
countries' marine zones. Before the border was established, a
``disputed zone'' existed where fishermen from both countries
fished side by side.
   Canada's tough marine enforcement was highlighted last year when
Canadian patrols fired at the Donna Lynn, a New Bedford, Mass.,
scalloper, after the vessel's captain refused to let officials on
board. The captain claimed his boat was in U.S. waters.
   Recently, another New Bedford boat was pursued by Canadian
patrols for 14 hours.
</TEXT>
