<FILEID>AP-NR-07-22-89 1231EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Philippines-Crash     07-22 0459</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Philippines-Crash,0477</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pilot of Crashed Plane Was Told Not to Land, Officials Say</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CLARO CORTES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The pilot of a Philippine Airlines
plane that crashed on a highway, killing eight people, did not
acknowledge instructions from air traffic controllers not to land
during a heavy downpour, airport officials said Saturday.
   An official also said the runway lights were out at the time of
Friday's crash, despite an order to turn them on because of the
storm.
   The twin-engine BAC 1-11 jet with 98 people aboard missed a
runway, crashed through a concrete wall, and bounced onto Manila's
South Expressway, killing eight people on the ground and injuring
91 people. One person was in critical condition Saturday.
   The plane smashed at least four vehicles when it bounced off the
12-lane highway and careened onto railroad tracks next to the
highway, witnesses said.
   It was traveling to the capital from Zamboanga City, 540 miles
southeast of Manila.
   Visibility was limited because of heavy rain, officials said.
However, no official cause of the crash has been given.
   When the plane was over the runway, ``the pilot was given
instructions to pull up, based on the analysis of the controller
that he was not going to make it,'' Rudy Flores, the control tower
supervisor, told The Associated Press. He did not say exactly how
high the plane was at the time.
   ``The pilot did not acknowledge and instead of pulling up, he
continued to descend,'' Flores said.
   Airline spokesman Enrique Santos refused to comment on Flores'
statement, saying an investigation was under way. Santos said
earlier Friday that the pilot, Capt. Ricardo Misa, had been cleared
for landing ``when the runway is in sight.''
   Misa himself was not available for comment.
   Rose Reyes, Flores' deputy, confirmed that the plane had
initially been cleared to land when the aircraft last radioed the
tower from five miles away. She said, however, that the rainstorm
got worse after that.
   Flores said the instructions to the pilot were changed when
controllers judged he could not safely land.
   The runway lights also were out during the mid-afternoon crash
despite the storm, Ms. Reyes said.
   At least 20 minutes before the crash, after skies darkened and
rain started falling in sheets, tower controllers told airport
electricians to turn on the lights to help guide the plane, she
said.
   ``They told us the lights were on, that's it's OK, but when we
saw that there were no runway lights, we called them again,'' Ms.
Reyes said. ``There may have been something wrong with the lights,
maybe the cables. We don't know.''
   Airline officials have turned over the plane's flight and voice
recorders to a five-man investigation team from the Air
Transportation Office.
</TEXT>
