<HEAD>Hooded Gunman Sprays Church, Killing Two Women</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 7th graf, `The injured...' to UPDATE with victim IDs. Picks
up 8th graf, `Another witness....'</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto LA2</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT JABLON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A hooded gunman dressed in black burst into a
Bible study graduation ceremony and blasted three people with a
shotgun, killing two women and wounding a man.
   The shooting Friday night occurred at a celebration for children
finishing a weeklong study class.
   About 50 people, half of them children, were at the Mount Olive
Church of God in Christ, which has been active in fighting drugs in
the gang-plagued neighborhood south of downtown.
   Police said they had no immediate explanation for the shootings.
   The killer, who may have had an accomplice, was at large today,
said Lt. Charles Massey.
   ``He had a mask on his face and a sawed-off shotgun,'' said
Nancy Wright, who spoke to a witness to the shooting. ``When he
started firing, everybody hit the floor.''
   Police today identified the victims as Mae Lee 76, and
Patronella Luke, 35. Mrs. Luke's husband, Peter Luke, 33, was shot
in the leg and taken to California Medical Center, said police Sgt.
Frank Mena.
   Another witness, who spoke to The Associated Press by phone from
inside the church said the congregation was listening to the
preacher when they heard two shots fired outside the church.
   A few minutes later, a man in a ski mask with a shotgun calmly
entered and shot three times.
   ``I was the first to face the barrel,'' said the woman, who
refused to give her name. ``I prayed, `Don't let him shoot me.' I
sat very still and he walked on.''
   A woman in her 30s was shot point-blank in the face. The other
victim was an elderly woman, shot as she tried to flee, said Ms.
Wright.
   ``One lady turned to run to the bathroom and he shot her in the
back,'' she said, citing the witness.
   The church is in an area plagued by gang activity, which police
have been attempting to control by deploying large task forces.
</TEXT>
