<FILEID>AP-NR-07-22-89 1405EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Soviet-Strikes Bjt   07-22 0846</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Strikes, Bjt,0872</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soviet Miners Reject Settlement, Other Industries Endangered</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos MOSB1, MOSB2</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANDREW KATELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Miners in the country's biggest coal field on
Saturday rejected a government offer to end their weeklong strike,
and reports indicated half the coal industry's 1 million workers
remained off the job.
   ``All mines have stopped,'' the Tass news agency reported from
the Donetsk Coal Basin in the Ukraine.
   Miners in one major coal center, Karaganda in the republic of
Kazakhstan, began returning to work after negotiators worked out a
settlement package, Tass said. But other strikes were depriving
vital factories of fuel and threatening industry nationwide.
   The Donetsk Basin has 121 pits with an annual production of 210
million metric tons.
   Miners, many in helmets and overalls, gathered outside
government offices in the city of Donetsk and rejected the pact,
which would have increased vacation time and paid workers for time
spent descending into pits.
   Western reporters said about 5,000 miners assembled to vote down
the deal. Strike leaders told a rally they would continue the
walkout because they didn't have faith the government would
implement the agreement.
   ``The strikers insist on the immediate satisfaction of their
conditions for retirement benefits for miners, which is not within
the competence of local authorities, and also that the government
guarantee fulfillment of their demands,'' Tass said.
   After learning miners had not accepted the proposals, President
Mikhail S. Gorbachev and Prime Minister Nikolai I. Ryzhkov sent a
telegram urging them ``to return to work, because the situation in
several economic sectors has reached critical levels.''
   The Kremlin leaders assured strikers their demands ``would be
reviewed urgently by the Supreme Soviet (parliament) and the
Council of Ministers, with participation by representatives of the
miners, to reach the necessary decisions,'' Tass reported.
   About 300,000 Donetsk miners have been striking since July 15,
holding out for more concessions than those granted Siberian miners
who began the wave of labor unrest July 11.
   The Siberian miners from the Kuznetsk Coal Basin _ the nation's
second-largest coal field _ returned to work Thursday and Friday
after they were promised pay increases, more consumer goods and
greater control over their industry.
   Officials have said the Kuznetsk settlement would apply to
miners nationwide, but the remaining strikers were holding out for
more concessions.
   Alexander E. Makarsky, a TV journalist in Donetsk, said in a
telephone interview a proposed settlement was reached Saturday
after two days of negotiations between miners' representatives, the
government and the official trade union. He said it included
earlier pension eligibility, pay increases and extended vacations
to 42 days, with even more time offered to miners working in
especially difficult or dangerous conditions.
   Miners currently get 27 vacation days, Viktor I. Alexyanko, a
strike leader in Makeyevka in the Donetsk basin, said in a
telephone interview.
   The Kuznetsk agreement also extended vacations to 42 days, but
the labor daily Trud quoted Donetsk strike leader V. Koval as
saying Donetsk miners want more vacation because their work
conditions are worse.
   Koval said Donetesk pits are two or three times deeper than
those in other regions and that temperatures in them sometimes go
above 104.
   Makarsky said another provision in the agreement would have
given miners pay for the time it takes them to descend into the
pits _ sometimes up to two hours.
   In Karaganda, negotiators reviewed 45 demands and signed an
agreement Saturday to end a two-day strike, Tass said. All miners
in the city went back to work and those in outlying areas, at 26
mines, were following, news agency reported.
   Among the demands of Karaganda miners were that nuclear weapons
tests be stopped at the Semipalatinsk range in Kazakhstan and that
destruction of medium-range nuclear weapons be stopped elsewhere in
the republic, according to Trud. The miners contend those
activities are harming the environment.
   There was no immediate word whether the government agreed to the
nuclear-related demands.
   The newspaper Sovietskaya Rossiya said miners remained on strike
at 11 of the 13 mines in Vorkuta in the Pechora Basin in the Arctic
and at all 12 mines in Chervonograd in the western Ukraine. Anatoly
Dotsenko, a spokesman for the Ukrainian Helsinki Watch Group in
Moscow, said the strike also spread to four of the eight mines of
Novovolynsk in the western Ukraine on the Polish border but that
miners there returned to work after a government representative
said authorities would meet their demands.
   The economic toll and threat to the coke and steel industries
was a major theme of Saturday's press reports.
   Sovietskaya Rossiya said the steel industry was in a ``critical
state'' because it lacked coal. A Karaganda steel plant director
warned he had only a day's worth of coal reserves, and steelworkers
in Pavlograd in the Donetsk Basin said they had only a two-day
supply, newspapers reported.
   Pravda said a boiler station and asphalt plant in Pavlograd have
shut down because of the fuel shortage.
   Trud said there was a threat of cave-ins and floods of water at
striking mines, apparently because maintenance crews were striking.
</TEXT>
