<DOCNO> AP890722-0093 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-22-89 1406EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-GayPolitician     07-22 0631</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Gay Politician,0650</SECOND>
<HEAD>Group Seeks To Recall School Board Member Because of Homosexuality</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICH CARTIERE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FREMONT, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A group has launched a petition drive to
recall the school board president in this San Francisco suburb,
accusing him of defrauding voters by not disclosing he is gay until
after he had been in office for four years.
   The Fremont Family Alliance filed recall papers last week
against board president Robert Stipicevich. The group has five
months to gather 12,000 signatures for a recall measure to be put
on the ballot.
   Stipicevich, who was one of the youngest elected officials in
California when he won a school board seat four years ago at age
22, says he disclosed his homosexuality at a news conference in May
because was tired of constant whispering behind his back.
   ``I think it's real important to say that I am not living a
lie,'' he said. ``There isn't an office in the land or a position
in the country that's worth it.''
   He called Fremont, a San Francisco suburb with a population of
more than 130,000, a ``diverse community and they're not going to
be bothered by this. It's irrelevant to the job I'm doing on the
school board.''
   In addition to defrauding voters, the Family Alliance says, his
homosexuality created a conflict of interest, arguing that he
should have abstained from voting on the school district's recently
enacted AIDS education curriculum.
   ``We're bombarded by the media emphasizing that it's OK to be so
liberal and that since the largest city in the area accepts it, it
must be so,'' said Ron Smith, a spokesman for the group.
   ``We don't want outside forces dictating how Fremont should be
run and the type of politics that should be here,'' he added. The
alliance includes some ministers, but no church organization has
officially backed it.
   The petition drive has prompted soul-searching in this town,
which was named 33 years ago for a pioneer explorer because its
citizens considered themselves a progressive community.
   His foes say community identity is at stake. Many feel the idea
that gay people should be open about their lifestyles in this
politically moderate enclave is an attempt to import ``gay
politics'' from San Francisco, 35 miles northeast.
   Fremont isn't the only city in the region concerned about gay
rights issues. An anti-AIDS discrimination measure faces a
referendum in nearby Concord, where similar charges of outside
influence have been made.
   And in San Francisco itself, a proposal to overturn the city's
domestic-partnership law has been placed on the ballot after church
groups circulated referendum petitions. The law gives homosexual
couples some benefits available to married couples.
   ``I hope it's a trend,'' said Smith. ``You're finding a backlash
because people have just sat still and finally something had to
happen.''
   He said that even though Stipicevich's term expires next year,
the group is seeking a recall vote to bring the issue before the
public.
   Stipicevich, a shipping and mail supervisor for a clothing
chain, recently received glowing endorsements from other school
board members. At the first board meeting after his announcement,
75 supporters showed up and gave him a standing ovation, and he
says he has received hundreds of letters of support from across the
country.
   But Stipicevich also has received a death threat, a few obscene
letters and the recall drive. Former City Councilman Ken Steadman
told Stipicevich at one board meeting he was exploiting children
because of his ``moral corruptions.''
   State Assemblywoman Delaine Eastin calls the issue needlessly
divisive.
   ``Bob did what he felt he had to do,'' she said. ``I can't make
that decision for him.''
   ``The question on balance is if Bob is making good policy
decisions, not whether he should have come out of the closet.''
</TEXT>
