<FIRST>r i AM-Uganda     07-22 0275</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Uganda,0281</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ugandan Officers Arrested in Civilian Deaths</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KAMPALA, Uganda (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Several military officers have been
arrested and accused of negligence in the deaths of 47 people who
suffocated when soldiers locked them in railroad cars for three
days, Radio Uganda reported Saturday.
   ``After preliminary investigations, it has been established that
a total of 47 people died as a result of gross criminal negligence
by the officer in command,'' the state-owned radio said, quoting a
government statement.
   Maj. Gen. Salim Saleh, the army commander, signed the statement,
the broadcast said. It did not give the names or number of officers
arrested, but said they included a brigade commander.
   The statement said the victims were among 238 youths detained
June 10 and held in unused railroad cars in war-torn northeastern
Uganda. The soldiers, who were fighting rebels in the area at the
time, had rounded up the people in villages near the city of Kumi,
155 miles northeast of Kampala.
   ``Those people who died were actually the innocent. The rebels
had already been screened after a cordon-and-search operation and
had already been taken to the brigade headquaters,'' the statement
said.
   On Monday, the government-owned New Vision newspaper gave
slightly different figures, saying more than 50 of 276 youths
detained in the wagons died. The newspaper said troops locked the
youths in the wagons for three days.
   The area around Kumi is home to two rebel groups _ the Holy
Spirit Movement and the Uganda People's Democratic Army. On Friday,
New Vision reported that government troops had captured 500 rebels
and seized 501 firearms of various types in seven weeks of fighting
in the region.
