<FILEID>AP-NR-07-22-89 1446EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Lebanon     07-22 0661</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Lebanon,0683</SECOND>
<HEAD>Overnight Barrage Demolishes Beirut Buildings, Kills 6</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto BEI1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MOHAMMED SALAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Apartment buildings burned out of control
Saturday and cars smoldered in streets carpeted with rubble after
nine hours of artillery battles across the capital between Syrian
and Christian forces.
   Police said six people were killed and 52 wounded overnight.
   Shellfire severed power cables and plunged the city _ which
usually gets one to two hours of power a day _ into darkness. The
only lights that illuminated the skies were the flashes of
exploding shells.
   Ambulances drove on sidewalks, hugging the walls of high-rise
apartment buildings for cover. Through loudspeakers they shouted:
``A civil defense team is in the area. Please notify us if you need
any help.''
   ``Over here! Over here!'' a man's voice echoed in the densely
populated west Beirut neighborhood of Zaidaniyeh. The rescuers
rushed in the dark in the direction of the voice to find a family
trapped under a demolished house.
   In the district of Koreitem, artillery rounds blasted a building
while inhabitants were in the underground shelter.
   When the shelling eased, Soumaya Medawar emerged from hiding to
find her apartment a pile of rubble. Unable to cope with the shock,
Mrs. Medawar, 68, suffered a heart attack and died instantly.
   The casualties from the shelling raised the toll to 440 killed
and 1,836 wounded in the 18-week confrontation between mainly
Christian troops under Gen. Michel Aoun, who heads a Christian
government, and the Syrians, who back a rival Moslem government.
   ``Several casualties remained under the rubble for quite a long
time, simply because no one had a telephone line to request help
from rescuers,'' a police spokesman said, insisting on anonymity in
line with standing regulations.
   The divided capital shook as Syrian gunners entrenched in west
Beirut operated their Soviet-designed 122mm BM-21 multi-barreled
rocket launchers that fire 40 projectiles a minute.
   The rockets blasted residential districts in Christian east
Beirut, the coastline to the north and hills to the east and
northeast.
   Aoun's troops opened up with 155mm howitzers and 130mm mortars,
targeting mainly Syrian military positions, but many rounds
ricocheted to nearby areas.
   The right-wing Lebanese Forces coalition of Christian militias
fired randomly onto west Beirut and its suburbs, sparing no
neighborhood in retaliation for the Syrian barrages.
   Thousands of people fled during a morning lull, carrying with
them whatever they could salvage of their belongings. Christians
fled toward mountain resorts to the northeast, and west Beirut's
inhabitants headed toward south Lebanon.
   ``I'll stay with relatives in the south for a while. I have to
find a place where one can get some sleep and stay alive,'' said
Rashid Makkouk, who works at a spare parts shop in west Beirut.
   Makkouk, 42, said his wife and two children ``went crazy during
the shelling last night. Dozens of rockets exploded within seconds
in our street setting apartments on fire and destroying cars.''
   Acting Prime Minister Salim Hoss, a Sunni Moslem who heads a
Cabinet competing for legitimacy with the Christian government
under Aoun, conferred by telephone with Saudi Arabia's King Fahd,
sources in Riyadh said.
   Fahd is one of the most influential leaders in the Arab world.
The Saudi monarch, King Hassan II of Morocco and Algerian President
Chadli Bendjedid are grouped in a an Arab League committee trying
to pacify Lebanon.
   Saudi Arabia is Syria's main bankroller. It also has good ties
with the pro-Western Christians.
   The latest round of violence in Lebanon's 14-year-old civil war
broke out two days after Aoun clamped a blockade of ports run by
Syrian-backed militias south of Beirut in an effort to recoup $100
million annually in lost customs dues.
   The Syrians and allied forces retaliated by besieging the
310-square-mile Christian enclave northeast of the city.
   Aoun, 54, a Maronite Catholic, escalated the confrontation by
declaring a ``war of liberation'' against Syria's 40,000 troops,
stationed in Moslem regions under a 1976 Arab League peacekeeping
mandate.
</TEXT>
