<FILEID>AP-NR-07-22-89 1450EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Italy-Politics     07-22 0358</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Italy-Politics,0371</SECOND>
<HEAD>Veteran Premier Comes Forward For New Italian Government</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY BETH SHERIDAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former premier Giulio Andreotti stepped forward
again Saturday to form Italy's 49th postwar government, ending a
nine-week political crisis prompted by Socialists' opposition to
his predecessor.
   Andreotti's government is made up of a broad coalition of the
five parties that have governed together for most of the 1980s.
   The new premier presented his list of Cabinet ministers to
President Francesco Cossiga on Saturday evening, said Sergio
Berlinguer, secretary-general of the president's office.
   Asked how long he thought the new government would last,
Andreotti told reporters, ``You never know how long a child will
live: one hopes a long time. We are looking toward 92.''
   The next general elections are scheduled for 1992.
   The 70-year-old Andreotti, a member of the center-right
Christian Democrats, became premier for the sixth time. He was
premier twice between 1972 and 1973 and three times between 1976
and 1979.
   Andreotti said Saturday his government would concentrate on
preparing Italy for 1992, when the European Community is to
eliminate trade barriers. Other priorities include fighting crime
and tax evasion and protecting the environment, he said.
   No major policy changes were expected, with the government
maintaining its strong NATO and U.S. ties.
   The new Cabinet has 32 members. Socialist Party official Claudio
Martelli became vice-premier, former vice-premier Gianni De
Michelis moved to the Foreign Ministry, former Bank of Italy
governor Guido Carli became treasury minister, and Christian
Democratic politician Fermo Mino Martinazzoli took over at the
Defense Ministry.
   Andreotti succeeds fellow Christian Democrat Ciriaco De Mita,
who resigned May 19 after Socialist Party leader Bettino Craxi
criticized his leadership.
   Cossiga asked De Mita to try to revive the 13-month-old
coalition, but De Mita failed because of continued opposition from
the Socialists. Two weeks ago, the president turned to Andreotti,
who worked closely with Craxi in previous governments.
   Andreotti's coalition is comprised of the same parties that were
in De Mita's government: the dominant Christian Democrats, the
Socialists and the small Republican, Liberal and Social Democrat
parties.
   The new Cabinet is to be sworn in Sunday.
</TEXT>
