<FIRST>r i AM-Iran-Drugs     07-22 0251</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Iran-Drugs,0258</SECOND>
<HEAD>Country Opens Its Biggest Drug Rehab Center</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iran's largest drug rehabilitation center
opened Saturday, the day before the end of a six-month grace period
for addicts to give up drugs or face prosecution, Tehran radio
reported.
   The broadcast, monitored in Nicosia, said the complex in the
western provincial capital of Hamadan will serve 5,000 addicts when
it is completed. The agency did not say when that would be. It said
the center now can serve 1,000 addicts.
   The center has two workshops where addicts can learn
professional skills. Another complex will open next month in
central Yazd province, the radio said.
   The report indicated the center was part of a rehabilitation
program run by a prison welfare organization rather than one of the
hard labor camps where officials have said 55,000 hardened addicts
will be sent when the grace period expires.
   Law enforcement authorities say they have identified 80 percent
of Iran's drug addicts. Official statistics show the country has
about 1 million addicts, but unofficial estimates put the figure at
double that.
   The government began a fierce anti-narcotics crackdown in
December following last August's cease-fire in the eight-year war
with Iraq.
   The campaign so far has focused on nabbing drug traffickers and
dealers. Nearly 800 people accused of drug trafficking have been
hanged since December and thousands of addicts have been arrested.
   A harsh anti-narcotics law that took effect in January mandates
the death sentence for possession of even small quantities of drugs.
</TEXT>
