<DOCNO> AP890722-0109 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-22-89 1622EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Chad-Libya     07-22 0480</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Chad-Libya,0498</SECOND>
<HEAD>Chad Blames Gadhafi for Failure of Peace Talks</HEAD>
<DATELINE>N'DJAMENA, Chad (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Talks aimed at settling a border dispute
between Chad and Libya failed because Libya's leader demanded that
French troops be withdrawn from Chad, President Hissene Habre said
Saturday.
   Habre and his longtime enemy, Col. Moammar Gadhafi, met in Mali
on Thursday and Friday for their first talks in seven years.
   The presidents of four other African nations who mediated
reported that progress was being made, but the talks broke off
Friday without an agreement.
   The main dispute involves the Aouzou Strip, a 45,600-square-mile
border area, thought to be rich in uranium, that Libya occupies and
Chad claims.
   Returning home Saturday, Habre said Gadhafi insisted on the
withdrawal of ``extra-African'' troops from Chad before any
settlement could be reached.
   Gadhafi left the talks without commenting.
   France maintains 1,500 soldiers in Chad to back Habre, whose own
army chased out Libyan occupiers from most of northern Chad in 1987.
   Chad's ambassador to France, Allam-Mi Ahmad, said Libyan
intransigence was behind the failure of the talks. He told the
French news agency Agence France-Presse that Gadhafi refused to
take the border dispute to the International Court of Justice in
The Hague, refused to demilitarize the Aouzou Strip in extreme
northern Chad, and demanded the withdrawal of French troops.
   ``The French army is in Chad at the demand of Chadian
authorites,'' the ambassador said, ``and will not leave until there
are no longer any threats.''
   The talks were mediated by the leaders of Gabon, Algeria, Mali
and Nigeria. Under a proposed agreement drafted by officials from
Mali and Algeria, Chad and Libya would have tried to settle the
Aouzou border issue by political means, meaning negotiations within
the Organization of African Unity, and take it to the International
Court of Justice if those attempts failed.
   It also called for a treaty of friendship, a pledge by each
nation not to attack the other and creation of an OAU observer
force to stabilize a year-old truce.
   All prisoners would be repatriated. Chad is said to hold at
least 2,000 Libyans, but Libya says it has returned all captured
Chadians.
   Sources in Mali said Friday that Habre objected to several
points in the proposed settlement, including the immediate return
of war prisoners.
   Since Gadhafi gained power in 1969, he has supported several
anti-government groups in Chad, Libya's southern neighbor. They
included Habre's own faction when he was a guerrilla leader.
   After a Libyan invasion, government troops and allied French
soldiers drove Libyan forces out in 1987. France, the colonial
power until independence in 1960, has 1,500 soldiers in Chad to
support Habre. Libya has kept its foothold in the Aouzou Strip,
which has been in dispute for decades.
   Last month, Habre accused Libya of preparing an attack from
Sudan, Chad's eastern neighbor, with Chadian dissidents. Sudan and
Libya denied the charges.
</TEXT>
