<FIRST>r i AM-Cyprus-Protest     07-22 0568</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Cyprus-Protest,0586</SECOND>
<HEAD>Turkish-Cypriot Court Sentences Greek Cypriot Protesters; More Demonstrations</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: Stands for story Philia-datelined story on news advisory.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALEX EFTY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A judge Saturday sentenced 10 Greek
Cypriots to three days in jail for entering the Turkish-occupied
sector of Cyprus during a protest last week. Outside court, Turkish
Cypriots protested the punishments as too lenient.
   Hundreds of Greek Cypriots, mostly women, continued a sit-down
protest outside the Nicosia headquarters of the U.N. peacekeeping
force. Hundreds more wrestled with U.N. troops at a buffer zone
near the village of Peristerona, 16 miles west of Nicosia, the
capital.
   The swelling demonstrations, the most prolonged since the 1974
Turkish invasion, threatened to undermine 10 months of
U.N.-sponsored talks on reunification between President George
Vassiliou, the Greek Cypriot leader, and Turkish Cypriot leader
Rauf Denktash.
   They are scheduled to meet again July 26, but Denktash has
indicated he may not attend the closed-door session because of the
Greek Cypriot protests.
   The 10 defendants convicted and sentenced Saturday could have
received up to 18 months in prison. Eight were also fined $100
each. Two clergymen were fined $200.
   They were in a group of 108 Greek Cypriots arrested by Turkish
authorities Wednesday while protesting on the eve of the Turkish
invasion. The other 98 defendants, all women, have not stood trial.
   Judge Gonul Orenen, in the Turkish Cypriot Nicosia District
Court, said she gave ``very lenient'' sentences to the men to keep
relations between the rival communities from deteriorating further.
   If the fines are not paid within 24 hours, the clergymen will
serve 10 more days in prison and the other eight men five more
days, she said.
   The 108 detainess were charged with entering a restricted
military zone and violating the borders of the breakaway Turkish
Republic of Northern Cyprus. It was proclaimed in 1983 but is
recognized only by Turkey.
   The sentencing was delayed when more than 1,000 Turkish
Cypriots, shouting ``Murderer priest!'' demonstrated outside the
courthouse.
   The crowd demanded tougher sentences when they heard Judge
Orenen's decision.
   More than 500 Greek Cypriots demonstrated in the buffer zone
near Peristerona, 16 miles west of Nicosia, to dramatize their
eviction from Philia, a Greek Cypriot village occupied when the
Turks invaded on July 20, 1974.
   The Turks invaded ostensibly to protect the Turkish Cypriot
minority in the wake of a short-lived coup by supporters of a union
with Greece.
   Philia is less than two miles from Peristerona. Its inhabitants
try to penetrate U.N. lines to reach their village every year on
the anniversary of the invasion.
   Greek Cypriot policemen, fearing a confrontation between the
demonstrators and Turkish Cypriots, tried to stop the women but
were quickly overwhelmed.
   Some 200 soldiers of the Danish contingent of the U.N. Force in
Cyprus manned four lines of barbed-wire barricades to confront any
penetration of the buffer zone. But the demonstrators argued and
scuffled with the soldiers and some 100 of them slipped through
three lines, only to be stopped at the last barricade.
   The protesters at Peristerona waved banners saying: ``We demand
our rights and implementation of U.N. resolutions.''
   That was a reference to a series of U.N. Security Council
resolutions calling for the withdrawal of 35,000 Turkish soldiers
and some 50,000 settlers from the north and the return of some
200,000 Greek Cypriot refugees to their homes in the occupied third
of the island.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
