<DOCNO> AP890722-0113 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-22-89 1707EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Angola-PeaceTalks     07-22 0441</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Angola-Peace Talks,0455</SECOND>
<HEAD>Angolan Peace Talks Suspended</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LUANDA, Angola (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Talks aimed at ending the nation's 14-year
civil war were suspended Saturday when the rebel delegation
requested consultations with their leaders about a proposal to
monitor a cease-fire, according to news reports.
   Reports on rebel-run Voice of the Black Rooster radio, monitored
in Luanda from the guerrillas' bush headquarters of Jamba, said the
rebels asked mediating President Mobutu Sese Seko of Zaire to allow
them one week of ``necessary consultations.''
   The talks, held in Kinshasa, Zaire's capital, started Wednesday.
It was the second session between the U.S.-backed rebels of the
National Union for the Total Independence of Angola and
representatives of Angolan President Jose Eduardo dos Santos.
   According to reports in Kinshasa the talks are to resume on July
31.
   The reports said the rebels wanted to discuss Mobutu's proposals
for a ``hot line'' radio link between Luanda, Jamba and Kinshasa to
help monitor a June 24 cease-fire agreed to by rebel leader Jonas
Savimbi and dos Santos.
   The talks were held behind closed doors but reports from Zaire
said the government delegation, headed by armed forces chief
Antonio dos Santos Franca, accepted Mobutu's proposal.
   There was no immediate confirmation from the Angolan government
or the official media in Luanda.
   Dos Santos withdrew his delegation from the first round of talks
in Kinshasa on July 1, after only two days, claiming the rebels had
violated the truce.
   Reports of cease-fire violations continued as the second round
ended on Saturday.
   The Angolan state news agency, ANGOP, reported that an
unspecified number of civilians were killed, wounded or missing in
guerrilla attacks in four northern and central provinces.
   The rebels have said government forces also have violated the
cease-fire.
   Both sides also are at odds about what they agreed to in the
accord containing the cease-fire.
   The Angolan government claims Savimbi pledged to leave the
country temporarily, while members of his movement return to
civilian life.
   Savimbi has denied that he agreed to exile and rebel spokesmen
have rejected integration, calling instead for the formation of a
transitional government comprised of members from both sides to
prepare general elections.
   The rebels have been fighting to share control since a Marxist
government took power shortly after Angola's independence from
Portugal in 1975.
   The guerrillas have not explicitly stated their political and
economic philosophy, but they generally are pro-Western, favor a
multi-party democracy with regular elections and appear to support
a mixed economy.
   The United States sends military aid to the rebels. South Africa
also provided support until it signed a regional peace accord last
December that required a halt to the assistance.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890722-0114 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-22-89 1713EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Suriname     07-22 0478</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Suriname,0491</SECOND>
<HEAD>Truce Signed in Guerrilla War in Suriname</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL VERSCHUUR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>AMSTERDAM, Netherlands (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A guerrilla war in Suriname has
ended in a truce that will allow the rebels to keep their weapons
and eventually join the South American nation's police force, Dutch
newspapers reported Saturday.
   Suriname and the Jungle Commando rebels signed the truce Friday
in French Guiana. The accord calls for an end to fighting that
reportedly has killed hundreds of people in the country's eastern
regions over the last three years.
   The truce was immediately criticized by Suriname's army, which
ruled the former Dutch colony until 1987, the reports said.
   The accord, signed in Kourou, French Guiana, says the rebels
will not be disarmed but instead withdraw to three locations until
they are later enlisted in a special police unit, the Dutch reports
said.
   In a statement released after the signing ceremony, the
Surinamese army demanded the rebel group surrender its weapons and
said its police role would be ``unconstitutional,'' the reports
said. The army's approval of the truce is regarded as crucial to
its chances of succeeding.
   The rebels are led by Ronnie Brunswijk, 27, who served as a
bodyguard to Lt. Col. Desi Bouterse, when he was Suriname's
military ruler from 1980-1987. Bouterse yielded power to a civilian
government after elections two years ago, but the Dutch-trained
army still has considerable influence in Surinamese politics under
a state of emergency in large parts of the nation.
   Brunswijk agreed to a cease-fire in late 1987, but skirmishing
continued in the guerrilla war until last month.
   The truce also calls for an end to the state of emergency and
for an aid program for eastern Suriname, where Brunswijk has his
power base among the 65,000-member Bush Negro minority.
   The Brunswijk group was never more than 200 soldiers strong, but
it effectively controlled large areas of Suriname.
   By late 1986, the conflict had flared into a major guerrilla
war, with Brunswijk troops nearing Suriname's capital, Paramaribo.
The rebel cause was strengthened when government troops burned
several Bush Negro villages suspected of harboring rebels in
attacks that left at least 35 people dead.
   About 7,000 people, mostly Bush Negroes, fled eastern Suriname
to neighboring French Guiana during the insurgency. The Bush
Negroes are descendants of West African slaves brought to the
country by Dutch colonists.
   Brunswijk is a Bush Negro and a Cuban-trained soldier. He was
Bouterse's bodyguard until being fired in 1986.
   Details of their falling out are unknown, but the war was seen
as a personal feud between Brunswijk and the 42-year-old Bouterse.
   After his dismissal, Brunswijk is said to have taken weapons and
ammunition with him. He robbed banks and gave the money to his
people, gaining the reputation of a Robin Hood. But in June 1986,
Bouterse's army attacked Brunswijk's village, and the Jungle
Commando was born.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890722-0115 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-22-89 1720EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-AndreottiProfile     07-22 0442</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Andreotti Profile,0454</SECOND>
<HEAD>Andreotti One of Europe's Most Experienced Politicians</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Italy-Politics</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Italy's new premier is one of Western Europe's
master politicians, a man whose career embodies the nation's
political development since World War II.
   Giulio Andreotti, 70, who helped draft Italy's postwar
constitution, formed his sixth government and Italy's 49th postwar
government on Saturday.
   The Christian Democrat became part of the government in 1947 and
has been a constant member since, heading the ministries of
defense, treasury, finance, interior, industry, budget and, most
recently, the Foreign Ministry.
   The original Teflon politician, Andreotti has survived numerous
controversies and formal inquests. ``Power wears down whoever
doesn't have it,'' is one of his best-known phrases.
   He is known for his brilliance, his dry wit and his remarkable
grasp of issues. A stooped man with protruding ears, Andreotti also
a favorite target of Italian political cartoonists.
   Andreotti, a Roman Catholic with close ties to the Vatican, was
born to a Roman schoolteacher and his wife and earned a degree in
law at Rome University.
   During World War II he became a protege of Alcide de Gasperi,
who helped found the Christian Democrat party and became Italy's
foremost postwar statesman.
   At the age of 28, Andreotti became undersecretary of state,
beginning a long career that earned him the nickname ``minister for
life.'' He was elected to Parliament in 1946 and has been
continuously re-elected to his seat.
   Andreotti has been premier during some of Italy's most difficult
postwar days, when right- and left-wing terrorism plagued the
nation and the economy slid. On the day Andreotti formed his fourth
government, in 1978, Christian Democrat leader Aldo Moro was
kidnapped by the left-wing Red Brigades. Fifty-four days later, the
politician's body was found in a trunk.
   While Andreotti maintained the country's pro-American stance and
firm ties to NATO, he became the first Christian Democrat premier
to accept support from the Communists to keep his government
afloat. The Communists nearly overtook the Christian Democrats in
the late 1970s but have since lost much support.
   Andreotti's career has been marked by controversy. In September
1984, he caused an international furor by speaking out against a
possible reunification of East Germany and West Germany.
   Domestically, he has been cleared in numerous parliamentary
inquiries into charges against him ranging from corruption to
obstructing probes of a 1969 bomb attack thought to be the work of
right-wing terrorists.
   The author of several top-selling books on religious and
political issues, Andreotti also is an avid fan of the Roma
professional soccer team. His interests range from Latin to stamp
collecting.
   Andreotti is married to Livia Danese. They have four children.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
