<FIRST>r i AM-Azores-Earthquake     07-22 0176</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Azores-Earthquake,0181</SECOND>
<HEAD>Quake Rocks Atlantic Islands</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PONTA DELGADA, Azores Islands (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A moderately strong
earthquake shook buildings Saturday on an island in this
mid-Alantic archipelago, but no injuries were reported.
   Specialists at the Azores University Volcanology Center said the
quake measured 6 on the Mercalli scale, which gauges the intensity
of a temblor as felt in a specific location on a scale from 1 to 12.
   They said the quake's epicenter was near Lake Fogo about 15
miles from Sao Miguel Island's main town of Ponta Delgada.
   No injuries or serious damage were reported from the quake,
which occurred at 5 a.m.
   It was the most serious of more than 100 earth tremors on the
island in the past 10 days. Scientists believe the tremors are
related to volcanic activity in the area.
   The Azores lie near the North Atlantic Ridge, a seismically
active north-south line where two plates of the earth's crust are
pulling apart.
   A major earthquake hit the Azores in 1980, killing at least 49
people and injuring more than 300.
</TEXT>
