<FIRST>r i AM-Pakistan     07-22 0272</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Pakistan,0279</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former Governor In Jail In Connection With Shiite Killing</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PESHAWAR, Paksitan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A retired general and former
provincial governor during military rule in Pakistan was jailed
without bail Saturday in a year-old Shiite killing.
   Fazle Haq, an ally of the late military leader Mohammad Zia
Ul-Haq, was accused of conspiring to kill Arif Hussain Al-Husseini,
a moderate Shiite political leader who was gunned down in front of
a mosque in Peshawar on July 25, 1988.
   Zia died in a plane crash caused by sabotage in August 1988.
Benazir Bhutto was elected prime minister in November.
   Haq was allied with Zia when he overthrew Ms. Bhutto's father,
Zulfikar Ali Bhutto, in a bloodless coup in 1977. The government
had the elder Bhutto hanged two years later on charges of killing a
political foe.
   Haq accused Ms. Bhutto of seeking revenge for his part in her
father's fall from power. Her governing Pakistan People's Party
denied the charge.
   Al-Husseini led the Party for the Implementation of Shiite
Teachings. The majority of Pakistan's 107 million people belong to
the Sunni sect of Islam. A minority belong to the Shiite sect,
which predomintes in Iran.
   Haq was martial law administrator of Pakistan's Northwest
Frontier Province from 1979 to 1985 when Zia called non-party
elections and the civilian government of Prime Minister Mohammad
Khan Junejo was formed.
   Zia had promised elections within 90 days of his coup but it
wasn't until 1985 that they were finally held. After those
elections, Haq was named governor of the frontier province.
   When Zia dissolved his civilian government in 1987, Haq was
appointed a caretaker chief minister.
</TEXT>
