<FIRST>r i AM-Britain-Glass     07-22 0236</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Britain-Glass,0242</SECOND>
<HEAD>Boy Taken to Hospital After Glass Found in Candy</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An 11-year-old boy was taken to a hospital
Saturday after he discovered glass in a bag of candy he had eaten,
and pieces of glass had been found in canned beans in a separate
case, authorities said.
   Police said the boy, who was not identified, later was released
from the hospital and was not believed to have eaten any of the
half-inch pieces of glass he found in his tube of ``Nerds'' candy,
a brand involved in a contamination scare in May.
   ``The pieces of glass were very noticeable,'' a police spokesman
in Dartford, southeast England, said on condition of anonymity.
   He said the store that sold the candy had removed other packages
from shelves but ``we are anxious to trace other packets.''
   In May, Nerds candies were removed from shelves throughout the
country after 130 reports of glass in packages. A cause for the
contamination was not found.
   In Barnsley, central England, six cans of baked beans have been
found since Friday to contain pieces of glass, said the
manufacturer, HP Foods Ltd. All were purchased at one supermarket.
   The company had withdrawn 100,000 cans and was investigating, a
spokesman said on condition of anonymity. He said no ransom notes
or demands for money had been received.
   Two major supermarket companies withdrew the baked beans from
their shelves, officials said.
