<SECOND>AM-Carreras Returns,0202</SECOND>
<HEAD>Carreras Returns to Opera After Illness</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MERIDA, Spain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tenor Jose Carreras, who fought off
leukemia with a bone marrow transplant in 1987, performed his first
opera since the operation Saturday, singing Cherubini's ``Medea''
in a sold-out ampitheater.
   It has been extremely hot in Merida, and Carreras reportedly
fainted several times during rehearsals. But he appeared to be fine
Saturday when he sang Jason's role opposite soprano Montserrat
Caballe as Medea.
   Four government ministers were in the audience, and Queen Sofia
was expected to attend one of two later performances, on Wednesday
and July 29.
   Organizers of the XXXV Merida Festival of Classic Theater said
all the seats in the 3,000-seat amphitheater in this western city
sold out the first day tickets went on sale. News reports said
scalpers had a field day.
   ``People have called us for tickets from all over the world,
South America, California, London and Switzerland,'' one ticket
official said.
   Carreras underwent bone marrow surgery Nov. 16, 1987, at the
Fred Hutchinson Cancer Research Center in Seattle, Wash.
   His first concert after the operation was in his hometown of
Barcelona in July 1988 and drew 150,000 wildly cheering fans.
