<DOCNO> AP890722-0124 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-22-89 1828EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-ScaryLanding     07-22 0383</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Scary Landing,0397</SECOND>
<HEAD>American Airlines Plane Has Hydraulic Failure In Landing</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-DC-10 Crash, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TULSA, Okla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An American Airlines flight bound for El
Paso, Texas, from Chicago lost one of its main hydraulic systems
Saturday, forcing the cockpit crew to manually lower the front
landing gear before landing safely here.
   The loss of the single hydraulic system on the Boeing 727 was
far less serious than the reported complete hydraulic failure of
United Airlines Flight 232 on Wednesday, said John Hotard,
spokesman for American Airlines in Fort Worth, Texas.
   The United DC-10 crashed in Sioux City, Iowa, killing at least
110 of the more than 295 people on board.
   ``Well for one thing, it's a different airplane,'' Hotard said.
``(The pilot) just had one of his systems failure and there are
several redundant systems on (the plane.)''
   Asked whether the failure of a single hydraulic system was
unusual, Hotard responded:
   ``Certainly it scared the hell out of us.'' But the pilot ``had
no trouble landing. He made a routine, perfect landing.''
   Flight 139 had 110 people on board, including the crew, and was
scheduled to make a stop at Tulsa International Airport at 1:12
p.m., The pilot radioed to the Tulsa control tower at 1:19 p.m.
that the jet was experiencing hydraulic problems and he couldn't
get the front landing gear down, Hotard said.
   ``There was a failure of what they call the System A hydraulics
system, and this among other things controls the raising and the
lowering of the landing gear,'' he said. ``And because this system
failed _ and we do not know yet why it failed _ the captain and the
cockpit crew had to hand-crank the right main landing gear. ...
It's not that difficult to do.
   ``When System A failed, System B took the backup for the other
sytems of the aircraft,'' Hotard said.
   There were no injuries reported in the incident.
   The plane, which was just over 40 miles northeast from Tulsa
International when it reported problems, landed at 1:58 p.m.,
Hotard said.
   The plane was towed to American's main maintanance facility. The
passengers traveling on to El Paso were taken on a separate
aircraft, Hotard said.
   The 727 will be overhauled and serviced to determine what caused
the hydraulic problem, he said.
</TEXT>
