<FIRST>r a AM-WeatherpageWeather     07-22 0334</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0345</SECOND>
<HEAD>Showers And Storms Sweep Much of The Nation</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Thunderstorms rumbled across much of the nation on Saturday,
sweeping through Arkansas, the lower Missouri Valley, the lower
Great Lakes and the upper Ohio Valley.
   A low pressure center in northeastern Missouri combined with a
couple weak upper-level weather systems moving southeast across
Oklahoma to create showers and thunderstorms.
   In Arkansas and the lower Missouri Valley, showers and
thunderstorms were developing early Saturday afternoon.
   Showers and thunderstorms moving along a warm front were
scattered through the lower Great Lakes region and the upper Ohio
Valley. The rain and storms also hit the southeastern United
States, mainly along the Gulf Coast and the southern Atlantic Coast.
   But the rest of the nation enjoyed dry weather, with clear skies
in the upper Mississippi Valley and the northwestern United States.
   Heavier rainfall totals for the six-hour period ending at 2 p.m.
EDT included 1 2@3 inches at Kirksville, Mo. The storms dumped up
to 1 inch of rain Saturday morning throughout southern sections of
Kansas City.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 55
degrees at Arcata and Crescent City, Calif., to 106 degrees at
China Lake, Calif.
   The low for the nation Saturday was 38 degrees at Baker, Ore.
   Sunday's forecast called for scattered showers and thunderstorms
from the southern Plains to the lower Great Lakes and the southern
and middle Atlantic Coast states, and from New Mexico and Arizona
to western Montana; numerous showers and thunderstorms from the
eastern and central Gulf Coast, in the middle Mississippi Valley,
and in northern and central Arizona; and sunny skies throughout the
rest of the nation.
   Sunday afternoon highs were forecast in the upper 80s and lower
90s in the southern and middle Atlantic Coast region; above 90
across much of Texas, much of the northern Plains and most of the
western United States; above 100 degrees in the southwestern
deserts; and in the 70s along the Pacific Coast.
</TEXT>
