<FIRST>r a AM-People-RoseKennedy     07-22 0299</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-People-Rose Kennedy,0307</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rose Kennedy Celebrates 99th Birthday</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HYANNIS PORT, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rose Kennedy celebrated her 99th
birthday Saturday night with roses, Irish tunes, chocolate cake and
her great granddaughter, Rose Kennedy Schlossberg, age 1.
   More than three dozen members of the Kennedy clan gathered at
the family compound on Cape Cod for the celebration, which included
a special Mass and Mrs. Kennedy's favorite cake.
   A pianist played the Irish tunes she loves, including ``Sweet
Adeline,'' which was the theme song of her father, former
congressman and Boston mayor John F. ``Honey Fitz'' Fitzgerald.
   Sen. Edward M. Kennedy presented his mother with 99 pink roses
and a note ``to the rose of all roses and the greatest mother of
them all.''
   Mrs. Kennedy is the mother of a nine children, including slain
president John F. Kennedy and Sen. Robert F. Kennedy. She can no
longer walk, and her vision is poor, but she is still alert, her
doctors said.
   Cardinal Bernard Law, the archbishop of the Boston Archdiocese,
visited Mrs. Kennedy earlier in the day, and her daughter-in-law,
Ethel, took her for a walk in her wheelchair along the compound
drive.
   Family spokeswoman Melody Miller said Mrs. Kennedy's seat for
the birthday celebration was in the center of the room, next to the
piano, so she could see all her grandchildren and great
grandchhildren and hear everything.
   Mrs. Kennedy's former doctor, Robert Watt, attributed her
longevity to prudent living _ she does not drink or smoke and has
always watched her diet _ and personal strength. Her mother also
lived well into her 90s.
   Michael Kennedy, 31, the son of Robert Kennedy, said last week
that his grandmother's long life stems from her faith.
   ``I think it's in the genes. I just hope I have it also.''
</TEXT>
