<FIRST>r a AM-ActressSlain     07-22 0311</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Actress Slain,0319</SECOND>
<HEAD>Detective Agency Hired to Find Address, Newspaper Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TUCSON, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The man charged with stalking and killing
actress Rebecca Schaeffer hired a Tucson detective agency to find
her address in Los Angeles, a newspaper reported Saturday.
   Police in Los Angeles confirmed that the firm of Anthony Agency,
Investigators, contacted them after learning of the death of Miss
Schaeffer, co-star of the defunct CBS television series ``My Sister
Sam,'' the Arizona Daily Star reported.
   Miss Schaeffer, 21, was shot once in the chest when she answered
the door of her apartment Tuesday morning. The actress also
appeared in the current film ``Scenes From the Class Struggle in
Beverly Hills.''
   Sources who asked not to be identified told the newspaper that
Robert John Bardo, 19, the defendant, hired the agency less than a
month ago.
   Officials of the agency could not be reached for comment Friday,
the Star said, but it was reported in the Los Angeles Daily News
that the agency could not find Miss Schaeffer and ``had to farm it
out to somebody else.''
   Sources here said no other agency in Tucson or California was
involved, the paper said.
   Bardo was arrested Wednesday after darting into traffic on
Interstate 10 in Tucson. His court-appointed attorney said Thursday
that he had decided to fight extradition to California.
   Bardo, who is on probation for an April domestic violence
misdemeanor conviction, is being held in the Pima County Jail on $1
million bond and is under a suicide watch.
   Police believe Bardo was trying to kill himself when he darted
into traffic.
   Bardo, a unemployed restaurant janitor, was identified as the
man near Miss Schaeffer's apartment before and after the shooting.
In addition, police in Los Angeles found a shirt and a paperback
book Bardo told investigators he threw away when running down an
alley near Schaeffer's apartment.

</TEXT>
