<FIRST>r a AM-Obit-Greenspun     07-22 0455</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Obit-Greenspun,0470</SECOND>
<HEAD>Las Vegas Sun Founder Hank Greenspun Dead At 79</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Ruthe in 2nd graf is cq.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LAS VEGAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Herman M. ``Hank'' Greenspun, founder of the
Las Vegas Sun newspaper, a one-time gunrunner and political
activist, died Saturday after a battle with cancer. He was 79.
   Greenspun, who had been ill for more than a year, died at home,
said Ruthe Deskin, a longtime employee and assistant to the
newspaper publisher.
   A gunrunner for a Jewish self-defense organization that helping
establish the nation of Israel, Greenspun challenged some of the
nation's most famous people in his newspaper, which had a
circulation of 99,000.
   His ``Where I Stand'' column was a front-page fixture of the
morning newspaper from its inception and he used the platform to
promote a variety of different causes.
   Greenspun gained national attention in the 1950s when his
newspaper went to war with Sen. Joseph McCarthy. He was charged
with _ and later acquitted of _ publishing and mailing matter
``tending to incite murder or assassination.''
   The incident arose over a newspaper column predicting the
assassination of McCarthy by one of the people he bullied, and
recommending he commit suicide first.
   Greenspun was closely allied with Howard Hughes in the 1960s
when the eccentric billionaire holed up in Las Vegas and bought a
television station from Greenspun and several hotel-casinos.
   ``Hank was courageous, compassionate and had knowledge we all
seek but seldom gain,'' said former Gov. Mike O'Callaghan, chairman
of the board of the Sun.
   Greenspun, born Aug. 27, 1909, in Brooklyn, N.Y., was the son of
immigrants and, on both sides, the grandson of Jewish refugees from
Russian-dominated Poland.
   He came to Las Vegas in 1946 to open a short-lived entertainment
magazine, and later became a press agent for the Flamingo Hotel,
which was built and run by the gangster ``Bugsy'' Siegel.
   Greenspun soon quit the Flamingo and invested in a small, rival
hotel-casino, The Desert Inn, where he also became publicity
director. His interest in the hotel, originally substantial, was
eventually reduced to 1 percent.
   Greenspun began his newspaper career by buying an eight-page
tri-weekly that was started by the International Typographical
Union in a dispute with the Las Vegas Review-Journal. The small
paper grew to become the Sun.
   In late 1947, Greenspun was recruited by Haganah, the Jewish
self-defense organization which had been formed in British-held
Palestine. Greenspun helped run guns to Palestine, which was to
become the nation of Israel in 1948.
   As a consequence, in 1950, he pleaded guilty to violating the
neutrality act, and was fined $10,000.
   In 1961, Greenspun's felony conviction was pardoned by President
John Kennedy, enabling him to run in 1962 for the Republican
gubernatorial nomination. He lost the race.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890722-0132 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-22-89 2217EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Korea-BomberSentence     07-22 0437</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Korea-Bomber Sentence,0449</SECOND>
<HEAD>Appellate Court Upholds Death Sentence for Confessed Communist Agent</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An appeals court upheld a lower court
conviction Saturday and sentenced a confessed North Korean agent to
death for the 1987 bombing of a South Korean airliner that killed
all 115 people on board.
   Kim Hyon-hui, 27, was convicted of violating national security
and criminal and aviation laws.
   She showed little sign of emotion and looked down when Senior
Judge Lee Young-il sentenced her to death by hanging.
   Government officials have indicated privately, however, that she
would be pardoned even if the verdict is upheld through the Supreme
Court.
   Several relatives of victims of the bombing cried and shouted
insults when Ms. Kim, clad in white jacket and pants, was escorted
by two female security guards into the packed courtroom.
   ``Bring back my son. Why did you kill my innocent son?'' one
woman shouted.
   Hundreds of security guards surrounded the courtroom and checked
all people to prevent violent protests by relatives or a possible
North Korean threat to Ms. Kim.
   The judge described the bombing as ``atrocious and unethical.''
   The defense counsel had argued that Ms. Kim should be given a
lighter sentence because, they said, she was duped by North Korean
leaders. Defense lawyer Ahn Dong-il said his client will decide
whether to appeal to the Supreme Court within a week, as required
by law.
   Ms. Kim admitted at several hearings to bombing a Korean Air
Boeing 707 that disappeared near Burma on Nov. 29, 1987, on a
flight from Baghdad, Iraq to Seoul. All 115 people on board died.
   Ms. Kim told the court that she had planted two bombs, disguised
as a radio and a liquor bottle, on the plane on orders from Kim
Jong Il, son and heir to North Korean President Kim Il Sung, to
disrupt preparations for the 1988 Summer Olympics in Seoul. The
Olympics were successfully held with a record 160 nations taking
part.
   Communist North Korea had denied involvement in the incident and
said the bombing was committed by South Korea to embarrass the
North. The nations have been bitter rivals since their land was
divided in 1945. They fought the three-year Korean War in 1950-53.
   In a nationally televised news conference last year, Kim said
she and another North Korean male agent planted the bomb on the
plane when they flew from Baghdad to Abu Dhabi, where they got the
craft.
   The two were arrested in Bahrain a few days later and took
poison hidden in cigarettes. The man died but Ms. Kim survived and
was later extradited to Seoul.
</TEXT>
