<DOCNO> AP890722-0134 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-22-89 2311EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-YoungWomanofYear     07-22 0268</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Young Woman of Year,0272</SECOND>
<HEAD>Judges Select Missouri Entrant America's Young Woman of the Year</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GARRY MITCHELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOBILE, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A high school senior from Missouri was named
America's Young Woman of the Year Saturday night, capturing the
$30,000 scholarship that comes with the title.
   ``It's more than I ever could wish for,'' said 18-year-old
Kristin Huxhold of Kirkwood, gushing tears. ``At first I didn't
think it was me. I am so shocked.''
   Miss Huxhold, whose parents both teach high school, was one of
50 teen-age contestants in the stage production. She also won a
$500 award for her interview with the panel of judges. She plans a
career in education and singing.
   Her mother, Sonja Huxhold-Nold, said Miss Huxhold plans to
attend the University of Illinois this fall. ``We were wondering
how we would pay for it,'' her mother said. ``Her first love is to
become a vocal performer.''
   The first runner-up was 17-year-old Lara Michell of Winchester,
Ore., who plans to become an attorney. An accomplished pianist,
Miss Michell claimed a $15,000 scholarship, plus a $500 award for
her interview with the judges.
   The second runner-up was California's Gretchen Handel, 18, of
Shafter, who received a $10,000 scholarship. She also hopes to
become a lawyer.
   The Young Woman of the Year contest formerly was America's
Junior Miss until the name was changed this year in a bid to
attract new sponsors to the 32-year-old event.
   The candidates are selected in statewide competitions in all 50
states. The judges' scores are based on scholastic achievement, and
personal interviews, among other things.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
