<FIRST>u a AM-BrownvsBoard 1stLd-Writethru a0589 07-22 0565</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Brown vs Board, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0589,0578</SECOND>
<HEAD>Court That Revived Brown Vs. Board Case Withdraws Decision</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS one graf after 9th, `Individuals on ...' with reax from
school board attorney; picks up 10th graf, `Rich Jones, ...'; SUBS last
graf with three of background.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOPEKA, Kan. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A recent verdict reviving the historic Brown
vs. Topeka Board of Education case was withdrawn without
explanation by a federal appeals court in Denver, baffling both
sides in the case.
   Attorneys for both sides said they found out about the decision
Friday and said they were unsure what the unusual action by the
court means for the Topeka school system.
   ``We're in the same position now as if no opinion had ever been
filed,'' said Robert Hoecker, clerk of the 10th U.S. Circuit Court
of Appeals in Denver.
   In 1987, U.S. District Court Judge Richard Rogers of Topeka
ruled that Topeka's public school district had no illegal,
intentional, systematic or residual separation of races.
   In June, the appeals court overturned Rogers' ruling. It said
the Topeka school system had not done enough to overcome remnants
of the segregated school system that existed before the U.S.
Supreme Court decided the landmark Brown vs. Topeka Board of
Education case in 1954.
   The appeals court ordered Rogers to devise a remedy for what it
called the racially identifiable public schools in Topeka.
   Topeka lawyers involved in the case said the new opinion they
found out about Friday was brief, stating without explanation that
the appeals court had withdrawn its opinion and vacated last
month's judgment in the case.
   ``No one seems to know exactly what this means,'' Topeka
Superintendent Gary Livingston said. ``We'll be meeting with our
counsel next week to try to filter out what the implications are.''
   Individuals on both sides of the case said all they could do was
wait for another decision from the appeals court.
   Charles Henson, an attorney for Topeka's Board Of Education,
said the action Friday meant the case would still have to be
reviewed by the court.
   ``My understanding is that this has the effect of restoring the
case as a pending one before the 10th Circuit Court,'' Henson said.
``The effect of this order is to say that Rogers' opinion is still
pending, or that the appeal has not been decided. As to what will
happen next, we'll just have to wait and see.''
   Rich Jones, an attorney for the plaintiffs, said the court had
been asking for several records from the U.S. District Court in
Topeka during the last few weeks.
   ``When I got this letter (Friday), it looked like an order
asking for another record. And lo and behold, it said they were
withdrawing from the decision made June 2,'' he said.
   The 1954 Brown vs. Board of Education case struck down as
unconstitutional the concept of ``separate but equal'' public
schools for different races.
   The case was reopened in 1979 when the parents of 17 black
Topeka public school children sought a decision on whether the
schools had eliminated traces of the segregated system.
   The group contended the district had not eliminated vestiges of
segregation. The parents included Linda Brown Buckner, who as a
student in 1954 gave the landmark case its name.
   The parents had pointed to seven elementary schools and one
middle school that they said had a disproportionately high number
of minority students.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
