<SECOND>AM-HUD-Brooke,0319</SECOND>
<HEAD>Report Ties Former Massachusetts Senator To Pierce</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Secretary of Housing Samuel R. Pierce Jr.
intervened with a client of former Massachusetts Sen. Edward W.
Brooke to get a HUD project approved, according to a published
report.
   The New York Times reported in Sunday newspapers that Brooke,
who was well known as a housing specialist while in the Senate, in
1985 was promoting a Boston engineering and management firm, Paul
Parks &amp; Associates.
   The firm, headed by Parks, a Democrat who is a former state
Education Secretary in Massachusetts, in 1986 and 1987 received
more than $400,000 in financing from a discretionary fund
maintained by Pierce, the paper said.
   Brooke told the Times that he recalled helping Parks in his
application to HUD.
   Brooke wrote in a Nov. 5, 1985 letter to Pierce, ``Thank you for
your personal attention to the Paul Parks &amp; Associates proposal,
for which he and I are grateful.''
   But Brooke told the Times he did not recall what role, if any,
was played by Pierce in awarding the money.
   The newspaper quoted Parks as saying he was unaware of the
letter but was not surprised it was sent to Pierce.
   ``Eddie may have written to the Secretary on my behalf because,
as I say, we're personal friends,' he said. ``I appreciate him
doing that, but I can assure you it was purely a thing of letting
Pierce know that we are friends.''
   In April, a HUD audit showed Brooke had received $183,000 from
clients seeking assistance under the Section 8 Moderate
Rehabilitation Program.
   The program was intended to encourage developers to rehabilitate
low-income housing. It was suspended for a time earlier this year
because of allegations of widespread political favoritism.
   A telephone call made to a listing for Brooke in Washington,
D.C., was not answered Saturday night.
</TEXT>
