<FIRST>r a AM-Obit-Collins     07-22 0333</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Obit-Collins,0344</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former Dallas Congressman Dies At Age 73</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KELLEY SHANNON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former U.S. Rep. James M. Collins, one of the
first congressmen to speak out against the Nixon administration's
conduct in the Vietnam War, died Friday of heart and lung problems.
He was 73.
   Collins, a Republican, represented the 3rd Congressional
District in affluent north Dallas from 1968 until he lost a bid for
the U.S. Senate in 1982.
   President Bush telephoned the former congressman from Europe
earlier this month to wish him well. Several other national
political leaders also offered get-well messages, including Sen.
Lloyd Bentsen, a Democrat, who beat Collins in the 1982 Senate race.
   Parkland Hospital spokeswoman Sue Mundell said Collins arrived
at the hospital July 11 experiencing breathing difficulties. Ms.
Mundell said he suffered from pulmonary fibrosis, described as
pneumonia with underlying lung problems.
   In 1972, Collins became the central figure in the trial of his
former top congressional aide who was convicted in connection with
an $18,000 kickback and payroll-juggling scheme. The former aide,
George A. Haag, claimed Collins devised the scheme, but the
congressman contended he knew nothing about the kickbacks and
payroll manipulations in his office.
   Haag was found guilty of all 23 charges of mail fraud and using
fraudulent House pay forms for the kickbacks and one count of
getting an ex-employee to lie to a federal grand jury to cover up
the scheme.
   Collins was never charged.
   Born April 29, 1916, Collins attended Southern Methodist
University and earned graduate degrees from Northwestern University
and Harvard Business School, where he was class president.
   He served in the Army, receiving the Medal of Metz and four
battle stars for bravery. Collins also was involved in front-line
combat with Hitler's army in World War II.
   He later became president of Fidelity Union Life, which he
transformed into a major national insurance company that sold for
$300 million in 1978.
   He was known in Congress as an ardent fiscal conservative.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
