<FIRST>r i AM-Panama-Opposition     07-22 0428</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Panama-Opposition,0443</SECOND>
<HEAD>Opposition Announces Resumption of Demonstrations</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RAFAEL CANDANEDO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PANAMA CITY, Panama (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Opposition politicans said Friday
they will hold more demonstrations to demand that their candidates
in the May elections be allowed to take office on schedule in
September.
   ``We are willing to go to the front and take the risks and
consequences of these acts,'' said Guillermo Endara, the opposition
presidential candidate in May 7 elections.
   The announcement came a day after the Organization of American
States called for a democratic transfer of power on Sept. 1,
followed by new elections. The decision in effect accepts Gen.
Manuel Antonio Noriega's nullification of the May balloting.
   International observers said Endara's slate won the election by
a 3-1 margin. They said Noriega, head of the Panamanian Defense
Forces and the nation's de facto ruler, had the balloting annulled
when it became apparent his candidate, Carlos Duque, was losing.
   The OAS mediated talks between the government and opposition
last weekend, but the opposition discounted the organization after
it announced its position on the political standoff.
   ``We should stop experimenting with international solidarity,''
Endara said. ``We, the Panamanians, are the only ones responsible
for our own destiny.''
   He said the opposition had been assured that the OAS mediation
``was something marvelous; but since it hasn't turned out to be
something marvelous, since it has not known how to grasp our
problem, we simply have to tell them goodbye and follow our own
path.''
   He did not say when the public protests would begin or what form
they would take.
   Opposition demonstrations, held frequently for several weeks in
1988 to demand that Noriega leave, often were broken up by riot
police using rubber truncheons and water cannons that sprayed a mix
of water and tear gas.
   After the May election, thugs beat opposition protesters,
injuring Endara and one of his vice presidential candidates,
Guillermo Ford.
   The current presidential term expires Sept. 1. Manuel Solis
Palma has been acting president since Noriega had Eric Arturo
Delvalle fired in February 1988, a day after Delvalle had tried to
oust the general.
   Earlier that month, Noriega was indicted in the United States on
drug trafficking charges. Noriega denies the charges and has
resisted U.S. political and economic pressure to force him to step
down.
   An OAS mission began working in mid-July to try to resolve the
crisis. The talks last weekend were the first between the two sides
since the election.
   Endara said opposition officials will meet soon to decide
whether to continue negotiating with the government.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
