<SECOND>AM-Haiti-Drugs,0194</SECOND>
<HEAD>Haiti Seizes 504 Kilos Of Cocaine</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   PORT-AU-PRINCE, Haiti (AP) _ Authorities Friday seized 1,100
pounds of Colombian cocaine with an estimated street value of $9
million and arrested two men, the independent station Radio
Metropole reported.
   The drug haul, in the town of Jeremie on Haiti's southwest tip,
was the biggest this year in the Caribbean nation, officials said.
   The Haitian Narcotics Bureau, assisted by local soldiers,
arrested Jean-Claude Jean and Mimose Gentille, both accused of drug
smuggling, the radio station reported. A third suspect escaped,
according to the report.
   Jean also was accused of trying to pay a $4,000 bribe to an air
force soldier, Radio Metropole said. The radio report said Gentille
was arrested in April on drug charges and released.
   A drug smuggling conviction carries a 15-year prison term.
   U.S authorities say Haiti is a key transfer point in the
narcotics trade between Colombia and the United States.
   The radio report did not say where the drugs were seized. Drugs
shipped to Haiti generally come in by boat, are flown out by small
aircraft to the Bahamas and then shipped to Miami.
