<SECOND>AM-Press Aide Charged,320</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former Aide to Roth, Rinaldo Charged With Bank Robbery</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man who once worked as a press aide to two
members of Congress has been charged with robbing two suburban
banks, it was learned Friday.
   Thomas Springer, 40, was charged Thursday with three counts of
armed robbery, two of the Maryland National Bank in Bethesda, Md.,
Montgomery County police said.
   He was arrested Thursday morning in a wooded area near the bank
shortly after what police said was the second robbery.
   Police spokesman Sgt. Harry Geehreng said a man carrying a box
entered the bank about 10:30 a.m. and handed a teller a note saying
that he had a bomb and wanted money. The man fled with an
undisclosed amount of cash through a back door.
   A customer chased the bandit, but lost him. A police dog later
located him and the money and an empty box were recovered, Geehreng
said.
   Springer, of Silver Spring, Md., was also was charged with
robbing the same branch on April 14 and a Crestar Bank branch in
Bethesda on May 12, police said.
   He was held in the Montgomery County jail in lieu of $50,000
bond.
   Springer was a longtime press secretary to Rep. Toby Roth,
R-Wis., the congressman said Friday.
   Springer left his press job in 1987, but was later given a
temporary assignment in the office, a Roth aide said.
   Roth said he gave Springer the temporary job ``because I felt
sorry for him,'' but that Springer then failed to show up for work.
   ``I am deeply saddened,'' Roth said, but added he was not
surprised. Roth said Springer's ``behavior had deteriorated,'' in
recent years.
   Springer also worked for Rep. Matthew Rinaldo, R-N.J., on a
temporary basis, according to a statement from Rinaldo.
   ``Tom Springer worked here for a very short time and while he
was here his work was satisfactory,'' the statement said.
   A Rinaldo spokesman said Springer was a press assistant for
about six months last year.
