<FIRST>r a AM-IndianRaid 1stLd-Writethru a0652 07-22 0538</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Indian Raid, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0652,0550</SECOND>
<HEAD>Reservation Closed After Gambling Raid</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 10th graf `A special ... with 5 grafs to UPDATE tribal
chiefs voting to hold referendum July 29th; picks up 12th graf, `Laughing's
casino ...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM KATES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HOGANSBURG, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   State police Friday kept a Mohawk
reservation sealed off from outsiders after a gambling raid that
left Indian leaders debating whether to legalize the casinos as a
revenue source.
   The community of Akwesasne on the St. Regis Mohawk Reservation
has been closed to non-residents since Thursday morning when 225
state troopers and FBI agents raided five casinos. The officers
confiscated an undetermined amount of cash and financial records
and arrested 10 people.
   It was the second crackdown in two months and the first
involving federal authorities on gambling at the reservation, which
straddles the St. Lawrence River along the U.S.-Canadian border.
Illegal casinos on the reservation employ about 500 people and
attract busloads of gamblers, authorities say.
   State Police Maj. Ronald Brooks said he was not sure when the
blockade would be lifted. He said police continued to restrict
access to the reservation because of the potential for violence or
hostage-taking.
   The Mohawks' reservation security force also continued to
maintain roadblocks Friday. Indians piled up logs on a state road
through the reservation and at other points used an overturned
flatbed trailer and a gas tanker to block the route.
   Art Montour, a spokesman for the security force, said the
confrontation might drag on for weeks.
   ``It has got to be resolved. Either they (police) drop the H
bomb, or they have to make some concessions,'' he said.
   Although police said the situation on the reservation was
volatile, a woman who answered the phone at the tribal council
office said the atmosphere was relaxed.
   ``Everybody's just going about their business,'' she said,
declining to give her name.
   A special tribal meeting was held Friday to discuss a possible
gaming ordinance for the reservation.
   Lincoln White, one of three tribal chiefs on the American side
of the reservation, said tribal leaders voted overwhelmingly to
hold a referendum July 29 on whether to legalize some forms of
gambling.
   White, a proponent of keeping the reservation's casinos in
business, said the plan would allow bingo, card games like poker
and blackjack, and roulette in Indian gaming houses. It would not
allow slot machines, he said.
   John Brunetti, a spokesman for the U.S. magistrate's office in
Syracuse, said the tribe could approve some forms of gambling, such
as bingo, but not slot machines and other gambling machines that
were the target of the raid.
   Tony Laughing, owner of Tony's Vegas International, predicted
reservation residents would authorize gambling in a referendum.
   Laughing's casino was among those authorities planned to raid
Thursday. However, police were unable to locate Laughing and an
armed group of about 15 Mohawks prevented police from entering his
building and the Bear's Den, another casino. Bear's Den owner Eli
Tarbell also eluded police.
   Laughing said casino owners have agreed to turn over as much as
60 percent of their profits to the tribe. He estimated the
reservation's seven casinos could add between $2 million and $3
million to the tribe's coffers.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
