<DOCNO> AP890722-0144 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-22-89 0646EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-InterstateDrugs 1stLd-Writethru a0673 07-22 0808</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Interstate Drugs, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0673,0832</SECOND>
<HEAD>Many Traffic Tickets Written, But Drug Arrests Few in I-95 Crackdown</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 7 grafs to UPDATE with arrest and citation tallies;
picks up 4th graf, ```It's doubtful ...'; DELETES now-outdated grafs 8
and 9</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SONYA ROSS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   A sweeping, round-the-clock crackdown along a major Maine to
Florida highway known as a drug corridor was called a success
Friday, but drug arrests were not as abundant as police had hoped.
   Almost 10,800 traffic citations were issued for offenses from
speeding to drunken driving during the 24-hour crackdown along
Interstate 95, police said.
   But the number of drug seizures and arrests numbered was much
lower.
   The International Association of Chiefs of Police, which
organized the operation, said in a statement Friday the operation
was the first time every state traversed by a specific highway
committed resources for a coordinated operation.
   The Washington, D.C.-based organization said 10,799 traffic
citations were issued and 100 drunken drivers were arrested. In
addition, 297 criminal arrests were made with 570 charges filed,
including 355 drug-related charges.
   ``This was a pioneer effort,'' the statement said. ``The numbers
achieved during the 24-hour operation likely mean that other
corridors in other states will be candidates for similar saturation
programs.''
   In drug arrests, 65,876 grams of marijuana, 5,671 grams of
cocaine and 340 grams of crack were seized, but police said they
had hoped to nab more drug traffickers. They said they believed
drug dealers were aware of the sweep, which ended Friday morning.
   ``It's doubtful anything was moving,'' said Georgia State Patrol
spokesman J.D. Coleman. ``It could have been the publicity ... or
they just all drove very safely.
   ``You always hope for a magnificent seizure on the highway,''
Coleman said. ``But we took some dangerous drivers off the highway;
maybe we saved some lives. That's the bottom line.''
   The effort was named ``Operation CoFlaMe'' because it was a
cooperative operation that ran from Florida to Maine.
   During the dragnet, a few stolen cars were recovered and
fugitives captured. A Jacksonville, Fla., man was jailed on drug
trafficking charges and Virginia state troopers seized 140 pounds
of marijuana from one traveler.
   In Virginia, 37 people were arrested on various criminal charges
and 2,461 traffic citations were issued, said state police
spokeswoman Mary Evans.
   Twenty-eight of the arrests were drug related, she said. Eight
people were charged with driving while impaired.
   Among the drug arrests was John P. Demorest, 40, of New Haven,
Conn., who was charged with possession of marijuana with intent to
distribute after police seized 140 pounds from his vehicle, said
Virginia State Patrol Lt. W.L. Bowman.
   During other stops, officers seized four grams of cocaine and
two grams of crack, a potent cocaine derivative, Ms. Evans said.
   In Georgia, troopers issued 484 traffic citations, 310 of which
were speeding tickets and 21 for drunken driving. In 20
drug-related arrests, officers seized 380 grams of marijuana, a
gram of crack cocaine, ``a fraction of a kilo'' of cocaine and
$1,526 in currency, Coleman said.
   ``For Georgia, it was not a major drug thing,'' he said.
   Officers arrested five people at a rural Georgia weigh station
and recovered a stolen car carrying luxury car parts.
   South Carolina's highway patrol reported more than 300 traffic
citations on its 200-mile stretch of I-95 by Friday morning, said
spokesman Brian Ellison.
   Connecticut state police netted 1[ kilograms of cocaine and
about 1{ pounds of marijuana. About 480 citations were given,
including one for drunken driving.
   Darien Cedric Wright, 23, of Jacksonville, Fla., was being held
without bail Friday after being arrested on drug trafficking
charges about eight miles north of Cocoa Beach, Fla. Troopers said
they found two kilograms of cocaine and 263 grams of crack cocaine
in his car.
   The drugs found in Wright's car had an estimated street value of
$62,500.
   ``Maybe this will have an adverse effect on criminals using our
highways,'' said Florida Highway Patrol Lt. Randy Brown.
   Police in Maryland seized 23.4 grams of marijuana, 66.7 grams of
cocaine and $890 in currency. Thirty-six motorists were arrested,
including one for a stolen vehicle and four on fugitive warrants.
   In Rhode Island, three people were arrested on charges of
possession of cocaine with intent to distribute, one was arrested
for simple possession and one trucker was arrested on a charge of
possession of a sawed-off shotgun, said Lt. Norman Pineau.
   He said Rhode Island police confiscated a total of slightly more
than one ounce of alleged cocaine.
   ``It's the first time ... that we've all participated in
something like this,'' said Rhode Island State Police Capt. Frank
McGee.
   Pineau said 1,148 people were stopped and 213 were issued
traffic citations, including 43 for speeding.
   The other states participating in the sweep were: North
Carolina, Massachusetts, Pennsylvania, New York, New Jersey,
Delaware and New Hampshire.
</TEXT>
