<FIRST>r a AM-Obit-Anderson     07-22 0249</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Obit-Anderson,0255</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former Montana Governor Dies from Self-inflicted Gunshot Wound</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HELENA, Mont. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Forrest H. Anderson, who ushered Montana
into a new era of government during his one term as governor, is
dead at the age of 76.
   Anderson died Thursday from a self-inflicted gunshot wound to
the abdomen, Lewis and Clark County Coroner Mickey Nelson said. He
had been in failing health for years.
   ``Forrest was not a coward; he was very, very strong,'' said
longtime friend and former state Supreme Court Justice Gene Daly.
``I would think he just got damn tired of being sick. I know he was
unhappy about being incapacitated.''
   Gov. Stan Stephens said he was ordering flags flown at half
staff to honor the memory of the former governor, adding, ``We've
lost a very dedicated public servant.''
   Andersen, a Democrat, served as a state legislator, attorney
general, and Supreme Court justice. He served only one term as
governor, from 1969-1972, but oversaw some of the most sweeping
changes in the history of Montana government.
   When he took office, government was run by more than 300 state
boards, bureaus and agencies. By the time he left office, it had 19
state departments and a new constitution.
   ``When he became governor, we had a government essentially from
the 1890s,'' said William F. Crowley, a University of Montana law
professor and former adviser to Anderson. ``And when he was
through, we had possibly what was the most modern governmental
system in the United States.''
</TEXT>
