<FIRST>r i AM-Brazil-Nahas     07-22 0355</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Brazil-Nahas,0367</SECOND>
<HEAD>Federal Judge Orders Arrest of Brazilian Investor</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RIO DE JANEIRO, Brazil (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge on Friday ordered
the arrest of multimillionaire investor Naji Nahas and former
Central Bank president Elmo Camoes for allegedly participating in a
stock scandal.
   Judge Augusto Guilherme Diefenthaeler of Rio's 13th federal
court said the two were accused of ``inadmissible manipulation'' of
the Rio and Sao Paulo stock exchanges.
   Nahas is suspected as the central figure in a recent stock
market scandal that forced the closing of six brokerages.
   Camoes was forced to resign as president of the Central Bank,
Brazil's equivalent of the U.S. Federal Reserve, when the brokerage
firm he owned was accused in the speculation scandal.
   In his three-page statement, Diefenthaeler said Nahas and Camoes
should be arrested to prevent ``the possibility of them committing
similar acts in the market through other investors.''
   ``The dimension of the problem would leave the law in danger ...
if the accused were to come and go freely,'' the judge said.
   Federal District Attorney Celia Regina Souza Delgado said
federal police began a nationwide hunt for the two Thursday night.
   Ms. Delgado had requested that Nahas and Camoes be jailed until
brought to trial.
   Nahas, a 42-year-old multimillionaire businessman and No. 1
investor in Brazil's $30 billion stock market, was the pivot of a
scandal that sent Brazilian stock markets into a tailspin.
   The scandal broke June 9, when Nahas failed to cover checks
worth $31 million to pay for highly speculative deals on the Rio de
Janeiro Stock Exchange.
   The stock markets went into a tailspin andthe government ordered
them shut on June 12 to avoid further panic. The government also
barred Nahas from leaving the country. The markest reopened the
next day.
   Six brokerages involved in the scandal were closed and Camoes
resigned days later.
   On June 26, the federal police charged Nahas with two counts of
white-collar crime. Police said he tried to take $20,000 illegally
to London in 1987, and borrowed $12 million in 1983 from a bank of
which he was a major shareholder.
   The charges together carry an 11-year prison term.
</TEXT>
