<SECOND>PM-Business Mirror, Adv 24,0602</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv24</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release PMs Monday, July 24</HEAD>
<HEAD>Valuing the Stock Market</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN CUNNIFF</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Analyst</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Relying on basic analysis of companies,
financial markets and the economy, Wright Investors' Service sent
several sharp warnings to its clients several weeks before the
crash of October 1987.
   The substance of those messages was the same, that the stock
market was grossly overpriced, had been for many weeks and was
destined to fall soon and sharply. Within a few weeks came the
biggest shakeout in history.
   Now Wright is issuing warnings again. The international firm
based in Bridgeport, Conn., says prices may have overshot their
marks.
   The new warnings don't have the urgency of those made in 1987.
Instead of flashing red, you might say, they are a steady amber.
But the sugggestion is there: If prices continue to rise the
signals might turn red again.
   Its forecast: ``While nowhere near as excessively priced today
as two summers ago, stocks are clearly still overvalued in light of
current bond yields and uncertain prospects for the near-term
economy and profits.''
   Consequently, it adds, stock prices may weaken during the second
half of 1989 while bond market values increase.
   Among the basic tools used by Wright in such analyses are
price-earnings ratios, price-equity ratios, dividend yields, bond
yields and the prospect for corporate earnings. The analyses
contain little that is subjective.
   PRICE-EARNINGS. Rising stock prices and the prospect of lower
corporate profits in the quarters ahead have caused the
price-earnings ratio of the Standard &amp; Poor's 500-stock index to
rise to 13.1 from 10.7 earlier in 1989.
   Those ratios are based on earnings expected for the 12 months to
come, and could be affected by unexpectedly higher profits. But
based on reasonable expectations, the P-E is now above its 20-year
average of about 11, although still well below the multiple of 16
times earnings in August 1987.
   PRICE-EQUITY. From 1.9 times shareholder equity at book value
when the year began, the S&amp;P 500 has moved up to a multiple of 2.1.
Over the past 20 years the norm has been 1.5, indicating a
substantial overvaluation.
   DIVIDEND YIELD. It is declining. The current 3.2 percent
dividend yield on the S&amp;P 500 compares with 3.5 percent as the year
began, and with 4.1 percent averaged over the past 20 years.
   In other words, the S&amp;P 500 is now priced at 32 times current
dividends, one-quarter higher than its average multiple of 25
during the past two decades. Obviously, says Wright, dividends are
giving little support to prices.
   BOND YIELDS. The spread between bond yields and the yield of
stock earnings has become more unfavorable for equities, a
consequence of rising stock prices and a slight deterioration in
the outlook for corporate profits.
   As the year began, the difference was 0.4 percent in favor of
stocks, a spread that compares favorably with the average for the
past 20 years. Today the spread is in favor of bonds, even though
fixed income yields have fallen.
   To move the relationship back to normal, says Wright, will
require a combination of lower stock prices, higher corporate
profits and lower bond yields. Fortunately, it adds, interest rates
are likely to continue to fall.
   In short, not an alarming situation, but one that prudent
investors should keep in mind as the Dow Jones industrial average
comes within 90 percent of its all-time high of 2,722 points, just
before the crash of 1987.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv PMs Monday, July 24.</NOTE>
