<FIRST>r f AM-KFCPresident     07-22 0278</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-KFC President,0288</SECOND>
<HEAD>John M. Cranor III Appointed President, CEO of Kentucky Fried Chicken</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOUISVILLE, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   John M. Cranor III, a top executive at
Pepsico Inc., was appointed Friday as president and chief executive
of the food and soft drink maker's Kentucky Fried Chicken Corp.
subsidiary.
   Cranor, 42, formerly president of Pepsi-Cola East, will succeed
Richard P. Mayer, who resigned to become president of General Foods
U.S.A., said D. Wayne Calloway, chairman of the board and chief
executive of Pepsico, based in Purchase, N.Y.
   ``We're very fortunate to have a leader of John Cranor's caliber
to succeed Dick,'' Calloway said in a news release. ``We have great
confidence in the entire KFC organization, and look forward to even
greater success in the years ahead under John's leadership.''
   KFC is the world's second-largest quick service restaurant
system with about 8,000 restaurants generating sales of nearly $6
billion. It was acquired by PepsiCo in October 1986.
   Cranor has held a series of marketing, operations and general
management positions in the restaurant, soft drinks and snack food
businesses.
   He began his PepsiCo career in 1977 as marketing group manager
at Frito-Lay, where he eventually served as vice president of new
business development and vice president of marketing.
   Cranor then was a senior vice president and later president of
Wilson Sporting Goods, then a Pepsico subsidiary.
   In 1985, he joined Taco Bell and became division vice president,
making him responsible for 1,300 restaurants in the United States.
He then became president of PepsiCo's Fountain Beverage operations
in 1986.
   Cranor was promoted to president of Pepsi-Cola East in February
1988, making him responsible for all Pepsi operations in the
Northeast.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
