<FILEID>AP-NR-07-22-89 0755EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>d f PM-Eastern     07-22 0724</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Eastern,0747</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eastern Files Reorganization Plan; Creditors Express Support</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: For Saturday PMs</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARCY GORDON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eastern Airlines' major creditors have expressed
support for the carrier's proposed reorganization plan, which would
give full repayment to creditors and to consumers holding tickets
canceled by the strike.
   Eastern filed its bankruptcy reorganization plan late Friday.
The plan provides that all Eastern's debts _ including outstanding
tickets _ totaling around $3.3 billion would be paid in full with
interest, mostly through cash payments.
   Consumers would have the option of either a cash refund or other
options such as tickets for other flights.
   The committee representing Eastern's major creditors in its
bankruptcy case said in a statement it ``supports Eastern's plan of
reorganization filed today with the bankruptcy court.''
   ``The committee is encouraged that the company has been meeting
its business plan and the committee will continue to monitor
operations through the ramp-up period,'' the creditors' statement
read. ``The committee looks forward to continued progress in the
case and to the emergence of Eastern from Chapter 11 as a
successfully reorganized airline.''
   Adam Harris, an attorney for the creditors' committee, said the
creditors would continue to support Eastern's proposal so long as
the airline's operating goals were met.
   But Eastern's pilots union warned that the airline still was
``far removed'' from securing bankruptcy court approval of its
plan. The union noted that, among other steps, Eastern still must
negotiate with the creditors over specific elements of the
proposal, which centers on a restructuring of the company as a
smaller, more efficient carrier.
   Friday was the scheduled end of Eastern's exclusive period for
filing a bankruptcy reorganization plan. The strikebound company
was not required to seek creditor approval before filing the plan,
but apparently did so to try to bolster overall support for the
proposal, which also must be approved by U.S. Bankruptcy Judge
Burton R. Lifland.
   Eastern has been in Chapter 11 bankruptcy protection from
creditors since March 9, five days after the start of a crippling
strike against the Miami-based carrier. The detailed reorganization
plan outlines how Eastern plans to emerge from bankruptcy at about
two-thirds its prestrike size.
   The airline wants to pay creditors with the proceeds of about
$1.8 billion in asset sales, including sales totaling $650 million
that already have been approved by the U.S. Bankruptcy Court.
   Some of Eastern's biggest creditors, and the amounts they are
owed, are: European aircraft manufacturer Airbus Industrie, $95.94
million; General Electric Co., $75.47 million; aircraft maker
Boeing Co., $53.98 million; United Technologies Credit Corp.,
$22.30 million; Rolls-Royce Credit Corp., $5.89 million; and hotel
giant Marriott Corp., $1.05 million.
   The scheduled expiration of Eastern's exclusivity period, during
which other parties to the case cannot file reorganization
proposals under bankruptcy law, was midnight EDT Friday.
   Lifland agreed early this month to a joint request by Eastern
and major creditors to extend the exclusivity period for two weeks,
through July 21, after they indicated they were nearing agreement
on a restructuring plan.
   Submission of a reorganization plan during the exclusivity
period automatically gives a Chapter 11 company 60 days more to
seek creditors' approval. Under bankruptcy law, competing plans may
not be filed during that period.
   Eastern's plan assumes that its Latin American routes would be
sold for up to $375 million, sources close to the situation said
Friday. They said Eastern has been in negotiations with American
Airlines for such a sale.
   A memo earlier this week from Eastern Senior Vice President Tom
Matthews to the Air Line Pilots Association said the route sale
idea would be scrapped if the company reached a contract agreement
with the striking pilots.
   Marathon talks between representatives of Eastern and the pilots
union, mediated by bankruptcy examiner David I. Shapiro, continued
Friday near Tampa, Fla., with no signs of progress, a source close
to the negotiations said.
   On Thursday, Lifland approved the release of $75 million raised
by asset sales to Eastern. The airline initially asked for the
release of $100 million from its major creditors, while a committee
representing the creditors asked that only $40 million be released.
   However, the parties agreed to the $75 million figure and the
judge approved it, with the understanding Eastern could request
additional money from the escrow fund, which contains $352 million
from the sales of Eastern assets.
</TEXT>
